{"title_page": "Progressive overload", "text_new": "'''Progressive overload''' is a method of [[strength training]] that advocates for the gradual increase of the stress placed upon the [[Human musculoskeletal system|musculoskeletal]] and [[nervous system]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Janet L.|last2=Amann|first2=Markus|last3=Duchateau|first3=Jacques|last4=Meeusen|first4=Romain|last5=Rice|first5=Charles L.|date=November 2016|title=Neural Contributions to Muscle Fatigue: From the Brain to the Muscle and Back Again|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5033663/|journal=Medicine and science in sports and exercise|volume=48|issue=11|pages=2294\u20132306|doi=10.1249/MSS.0000000000000923|issn=0195-9131|pmc=5033663|pmid=27003703}}</ref> The principle of progressive overload suggests that the continual increase in the total workload during training sessions will stimulate muscle growth and strength gain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Todd|first=Janice S.|last2=Shurley|first2=Jason P.|last3=Todd|first3=Terry C.|title=Thomas L. DeLorme and the Science of Progressive Resistance Exercise|url=https://www.academia.edu/23449310/Thomas_L._DeLorme_and_the_Science_of_Progressive_Resistance_Exercise|journal=Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research|language=en|volume=26|issue=11|pages=2913\u20132923|issn=1064-8011}}</ref>.\n\nThe method was developed by Thomas Delorme, M.D. while he rehabilitated soldiers after [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Progressive Overload |chapterurl={{Google books|cLz_mwWQXucC|page=33|plainurl=yes}} |pages=33\u20136 |first1=William J. |last1=Kraemer |first2=Steven J. |last2=Fleck |year=2007 |title=Optimizing Strength Training: Designing Nonlinear Periodization Workouts |publisher=Human Kinetics |isbn=978-0-7360-6068-4 }}</ref> The technique is recognized as a fundamental principle for success in various forms of [[strength training]] programs including [[fitness training]], [[weight training|weight lifting]], [[high intensity training]] and [[physical therapy]] programs.\n\n==Scientific principles==\nA common goal for strength-training programs is to increase or to maintain one's physical strength or muscle mass. In order to achieve more strength, as opposed to maintaining current strength capacity, [[Muscle|muscles]] need to be stressed in such a way that triggers the body's natural, adaptive response to new demands placed on it.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nProgressive overload not only stimulates [[muscle hypertrophy]], but it also stimulates the development of stronger and denser bones, ligaments, tendons and cartilage. Progressive overload also incrementally increases blood flow to regions of the body exercised and stimulates more responsive nerve connections between the brain and the muscles involved.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nConversely, decreased use of the muscle results in incremental loss of mass and strength, known as [[muscular atrophy]] (see [[atrophy]] and [[muscle atrophy]]). Sedentary people often lose a pound or more of muscle annually.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe loss of 10 pounds of muscle per decade is one consequence of a [[sedentary lifestyle]]. The adaptive processes of the human body will only respond if continually called upon to exert greater force to meet higher physiological demands.<ref name=\"ACSM 1 Progression Models\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kraemer WJ, Adams K, Cafarelli E, Dudley GA, Dooly C, Feigenbaum MS, Fleck SJ, Franklin B, Fry AC, Hoffman JR, Newton RU, Potteiger J, Stone MH, Ratamess NA, Triplett-McBride T |title=American College of Sports Medicine position stand. Progression models in resistance training for healthy adults |journal=Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=364\u201380 |year=2002 |pmid=11828249 |doi=10.1097/00005768-200202000-00027 }}</ref>\n\n==Methodology==\nIn order to minimize injury and maximize results, the novice begins at a comfortable level of muscular intensity and advances towards overload of the muscles over the course of the exercise program.<ref name=\"ACSM 1 Progression Models\"/><ref name=\"ASCM 2 Trainers\">{{cite journal |title=The team physician and conditioning of athletes for sports: a consensus statement |journal=Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise |volume=33 |issue=10 |pages=1789\u201393 |year=2001 |pmid=11581568 |author1=American Academy of Family Physicians |author2=American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |author3=American College of Sports Medicine |author4=American Orthopaedic Society for Sports Medicine |author5=American Osteopathic Academy of Sports Medicine |author6=American Medical Society for Sports Medicine |doi=10.1097/00005768-200110000-00027 }}</ref> Progressive overload requires a gradual increase in volume, intensity, frequency or time in order to achieve the targeted goal of the user. In this context, volume and intensity are defined as follows:<ref name=\"ASCM 2 Trainers\"/>\n\n* '''Volume''' is the total number of repetitions multiplied by the resistance used as performed in specific periods of time.\n* '''Intensity''' is the percent value of maximal functional capacity, or expressed as percent repetition maximum.\n\nThis technique results in greater gains in physical strength and muscular growth, but there are limits. An excess of training stimuli can lead to the problem of [[overtraining]].<ref name=\"ACSM 3 Overtrain\">{{cite web |title=Overtraining With Resistance Exercise |first1=Andrew C. |last1=Fry |publisher=American College of Sports Medicine |url=http://acsm.org/docs/current-comments/overtrainwithresistance.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030075304/http://acsm.org/docs/current-comments/overtrainwithresistance.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2012 }}</ref> Overtraining is the decline in training performance over the course of a training program, often accompanied by an increased risk of illness or injury or a decreased desire to exercise. To help avoid this problem, the technique of [[Sports periodization|periodization]] is applied. Periodization in the context of fitness or strength training programs means scheduling for adequate recovery time between training sessions, and for variety over the course of a long-term program. Motivation can be maintained by avoiding the [[Boredom|monotony]] of repeating identical exercise routines.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Hass |first1=Christopher J. |last2=Feigenbaum |first2=Matthew S. |last3=Franklin |first3=Barry A. |title=Prescription of Resistance Training for Healthy Populations |journal=Sports Medicine |volume=31 |issue=14 |pages=953\u201364 |year=2001 |pmid=11735680 |doi=10.2165/00007256-200131140-00001 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Mi-Joung |last2=Kilbreath |first2=Sharon L. |last3=Singh |first3=Maria Fiatarone |last4=Zeman |first4=Brian |last5=Davis |first5=Glen M. |title=Effect of Progressive Resistance Training on Muscle Performance after Chronic Stroke |journal=Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=23\u201334 |year=2010 |pmid=20010133 |doi=10.1249/MSS.0b013e3181b07a31 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vannucci |first1=Robert C. |last2=Brucklacher |first2=Robert M. |last3=Vannucci |first3=Susan J. |title=Intracellular calcium accumulation during the evolution of hypoxic\u2013ischemic brain damage in the immature rat |journal=Developmental Brain Research |volume=126 |issue=1 |pages=117\u201320 |year=2001 |pmid=11172893 |doi=10.1016/S0165-3806(00)00135-8 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kraemer |first1=William J. |last2=Ratamess |first2=Nicholas A. |last3=French |first3=Duncan N. |title=Resistance training for health and performance |journal=Current Sports Medicine Reports |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=165\u201371 |year=2002 |pmid=12831709 |doi=10.1249/00149619-200206000-00007 }}\n\n[[Category:Physical exercise]]\n", "text_old": "'''Progressive overload''' is a method of [[strength training]] that advocates for the gradual increase of the stress placed upon the [[Human musculoskeletal system|musculoskeletal]] and [[nervous system]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Janet L.|last2=Amann|first2=Markus|last3=Duchateau|first3=Jacques|last4=Meeusen|first4=Romain|last5=Rice|first5=Charles L.|date=November 2016|title=Neural Contributions to Muscle Fatigue: From the Brain to the Muscle and Back Again|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5033663/|journal=Medicine and science in sports and exercise|volume=48|issue=11|pages=2294\u20132306|doi=10.1249/MSS.0000000000000923|issn=0195-9131|pmc=5033663|pmid=27003703}}</ref> The principle of progressive overload suggests that the continual increase in the total workload during training sessions will stimulate muscle growth and strength gain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Todd|first=Janice S.|last2=Shurley|first2=Jason P.|last3=Todd|first3=Terry C.|title=Thomas L. DeLorme and the Science of Progressive Resistance Exercise|url=https://www.academia.edu/23449310/Thomas_L._DeLorme_and_the_Science_of_Progressive_Resistance_Exercise|journal=Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research|language=en|volume=26|issue=11|pages=2913\u20132923|issn=1064-8011}}</ref>.\n\nThe method was developed by Thomas Delorme, M.D. while he rehabilitated soldiers after [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Progressive Overload |chapterurl={{Google books|cLz_mwWQXucC|page=33|plainurl=yes}} |pages=33\u20136 |first1=William J. |last1=Kraemer |first2=Steven J. |last2=Fleck |year=2007 |title=Optimizing Strength Training: Designing Nonlinear Periodization Workouts |publisher=Human Kinetics |isbn=978-0-7360-6068-4 }}</ref> The technique is recognized as a fundamental principle for success in various forms of [[strength training]] programs including [[fitness training]], [[weight training|weight lifting]], [[high intensity training]] and [[physical therapy]] programs.\n\n==Scientific principles==\nA common goal for strength-training programs is to increase or to maintain one's physical strength or muscle mass. In order to achieve more strength, as opposed to maintaining current strength capacity, muscles (see [[skeletal muscles]]) need to be stressed in such a way that triggers the body's natural, adaptive response to new demands placed on it.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nProgressive overload not only stimulates [[muscle hypertrophy]], but it also stimulates the development of stronger and denser bones, ligaments, tendons and cartilage. Progressive overload also incrementally increases blood flow to regions of the body exercised and stimulates more responsive nerve connections between the brain and the muscles involved.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nConversely, decreased use of the muscle results in incremental loss of mass and strength, known as [[muscular atrophy]] (see [[atrophy]] and [[muscle atrophy]]). Sedentary people often lose a pound or more of muscle annually.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe loss of 10 pounds of muscle per decade is one consequence of a [[sedentary lifestyle]]. The adaptive processes of the human body will only respond if continually called upon to exert greater force to meet higher physiological demands.<ref name=\"ACSM 1 Progression Models\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kraemer WJ, Adams K, Cafarelli E, Dudley GA, Dooly C, Feigenbaum MS, Fleck SJ, Franklin B, Fry AC, Hoffman JR, Newton RU, Potteiger J, Stone MH, Ratamess NA, Triplett-McBride T |title=American College of Sports Medicine position stand. Progression models in resistance training for healthy adults |journal=Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=364\u201380 |year=2002 |pmid=11828249 |doi=10.1097/00005768-200202000-00027 }}</ref>\n\n==Methodology==\nIn order to minimize injury and maximize results, the novice begins at a comfortable level of muscular intensity and advances towards overload of the muscles over the course of the exercise program.<ref name=\"ACSM 1 Progression Models\"/><ref name=\"ASCM 2 Trainers\">{{cite journal |title=The team physician and conditioning of athletes for sports: a consensus statement |journal=Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise |volume=33 |issue=10 |pages=1789\u201393 |year=2001 |pmid=11581568 |author1=American Academy of Family Physicians |author2=American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |author3=American College of Sports Medicine |author4=American Orthopaedic Society for Sports Medicine |author5=American Osteopathic Academy of Sports Medicine |author6=American Medical Society for Sports Medicine |doi=10.1097/00005768-200110000-00027 }}</ref> Progressive overload requires a gradual increase in volume, intensity, frequency or time in order to achieve the targeted goal of the user. In this context, volume and intensity are defined as follows:<ref name=\"ASCM 2 Trainers\"/>\n\n* '''Volume''' is the total number of repetitions multiplied by the resistance used as performed in specific periods of time.\n* '''Intensity''' is the percent value of maximal functional capacity, or expressed as percent repetition maximum.\n\nThis technique results in greater gains in physical strength and muscular growth, but there are limits. An excess of training stimuli can lead to the problem of [[overtraining]].<ref name=\"ACSM 3 Overtrain\">{{cite web |title=Overtraining With Resistance Exercise |first1=Andrew C. |last1=Fry |publisher=American College of Sports Medicine |url=http://acsm.org/docs/current-comments/overtrainwithresistance.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030075304/http://acsm.org/docs/current-comments/overtrainwithresistance.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2012 }}</ref> Overtraining is the decline in training performance over the course of a training program, often accompanied by an increased risk of illness or injury or a decreased desire to exercise. To help avoid this problem, the technique of [[Sports periodization|periodization]] is applied. Periodization in the context of fitness or strength training programs means scheduling for adequate recovery time between training sessions, and for variety over the course of a long-term program. Motivation can be maintained by avoiding the [[Boredom|monotony]] of repeating identical exercise routines.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Hass |first1=Christopher J. |last2=Feigenbaum |first2=Matthew S. |last3=Franklin |first3=Barry A. |title=Prescription of Resistance Training for Healthy Populations |journal=Sports Medicine |volume=31 |issue=14 |pages=953\u201364 |year=2001 |pmid=11735680 |doi=10.2165/00007256-200131140-00001 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Mi-Joung |last2=Kilbreath |first2=Sharon L. |last3=Singh |first3=Maria Fiatarone |last4=Zeman |first4=Brian |last5=Davis |first5=Glen M. |title=Effect of Progressive Resistance Training on Muscle Performance after Chronic Stroke |journal=Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=23\u201334 |year=2010 |pmid=20010133 |doi=10.1249/MSS.0b013e3181b07a31 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vannucci |first1=Robert C. |last2=Brucklacher |first2=Robert M. |last3=Vannucci |first3=Susan J. |title=Intracellular calcium accumulation during the evolution of hypoxic\u2013ischemic brain damage in the immature rat |journal=Developmental Brain Research |volume=126 |issue=1 |pages=117\u201320 |year=2001 |pmid=11172893 |doi=10.1016/S0165-3806(00)00135-8 }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kraemer |first1=William J. |last2=Ratamess |first2=Nicholas A. |last3=French |first3=Duncan N. |title=Resistance training for health and performance |journal=Current Sports Medicine Reports |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=165\u201371 |year=2002 |pmid=12831709 |doi=10.1249/00149619-200206000-00007 }}\n\n[[Category:Physical exercise]]\n", "name_user": "Victoragsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_overload"}
{"title_page": "C. Sankaran Nair", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sir Chettur Sankaran Nair\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]]\n| image = SirChetturSankaranNair.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1857|07|11}}\n| birth_place = Chettur, [[Kerala]], [[India]]\n| residence = \n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1934|04|24|1857|07|11}}\n| death_place = [[Madras]], [[British India]]\n| office1 = Advocate General of the [[Madras Presidency]]\n| term_start1 = 1906\n| term_end1 = 1908\n| predecessor1 = [[C. A. White]]\n| successor1 = [[P. S. Sivaswami Iyer]]\n| office2 = [[Indian National Congress|President of Indian National Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 1897\n| term_end2 = 1897\n| predecessor2 = [[Rahimtulla M. Sayani]]\n| successor2 = [[Anandamohan Bose]]\n| party = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| profession = Lawyer, jurist, activist, politician\n| footnotes = \n| signature = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Chettur Sankaran Nair''', [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]] (11 July 1857 \u2013 24 April 1934) was the President of the [[Indian National Congress]] in 1897 held at [[Amravati]]. Until present he is the only [[Keralite]] to hold the post.<ref>[http://www.congress.org.in/new/past-president-detail.php?id=11 All India Congress Committee \u2013 AICC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906202647/http://www.congress.org.in/new/past-president-detail.php?id=11 |date=2010-09-06 }}. Congress.org.in. Retrieved on 2012-06-11.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChettur Sankaran Nair was born on 11 July 1857 in Chettur family in [[Mankara]], [[Palakkad District]], as the son of Manmayil Ramunni Panicker and Parvathy Amma Chettur. His early education began in the traditional style at home and continued in schools in Malabar, till he passed the Arts examination with a first class from the Provincial School at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. Then he joined the Presidency College, Madras. In 1877 he took his Arts degree, and two years later secured the Law degree from the Madras Law College.\n\n==Career==\nNair started as a lawyer in 1880 in the High Court of Madras. In 1884, the [[Madras Province|Madras]] Government appointed him as a member of the Committee for an enquiry into the [[Malabar (Northern Kerala)|state of Malabar]]. Till 1908, he was the [[Advocate-General]] to the Government and an Acting Judge from time to time. In 1908, he became a permanent Judge in the High Court of Madras and held the post till 1915. He was a part of the bench that tried [[Collector Ashe]] murder case along with [[C. A. White]], then the Chief Justice of Madras, [[William Ayling (judge)|William Ayling]], as a special case.<ref>[http://madrasmusings.com/Vol%2019%20No%208/The_Ashe_murder_case.html We care for Madras that is Chennai]. Madras Musings (1911-06-17). Retrieved on 2012-06-11.</ref>\n\nIn the meantime, in 1902, the Viceroy [[Lord Curzon]] appointed him Secretary to the [[Raleigh University Commission]]. In recognition of his services, he was appointed a [[Companion of the Indian Empire]] by the King-Emperor in 1904<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/27688/supplements/4010 ''London Gazette'', 21 June 1904]</ref> and in 1912 he was knighted.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/28626/supplements/5082 ''London Gazette'', 12 July 1912]</ref> He became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council|Viceroy's Council]] in 1915 with the charge of the Education portfolio. As member, he wrote in 1919 two famous Minutes of Dissent in the Despatches on Indian Constitutional Reforms, pointing out the various defects of British rule in India and suggesting reforms. For an Indian to offer such criticism and make such demands was incredible in those days. The British government accepted most of his recommendations.Nair resigned from the Viceroy's Council in the aftermath of Jalianwalabagh massacre in April 13, 1919,but went to London and joined the Indian Council of States, as a member, remaining in the position till 1925. While there, he wrote the infamous book, ''Gandhi and Anarchy'',in 1922,tarnishing the popular image of Mahatma Gandhi. It is the only book he has written. Nair was a vehement critic of Gandhi,as pointed out by Ramachandra Guha,in ''Gandhi:The Years that Changed the World''.Ramachadran,Editor and writer had pointed out in Madhyamam Weekly that Nair had been a British agent. While Rabindra Nath Tagore returned the knighthood after Jalianwala bagh massacre, Nair kept and cherished it.\n\nHe played an active part in the Indian National movement which was gathering force in those days. In 1897, when the First Provincial Conference met in Madras, he was invited to preside over it. The same year, when the [[Indian National Congress]] assembled at [[Amaravathi]], he was chosen its president. In a masterly address, he referred to the highhandedness of foreign administration, called for reforms and asked for self-government for India with Dominion Status. In 1900, he was a member of the [[Madras Legislative Council]]. His official life from 1908 to 1921 interrupted his activities as a free political worker. In 1928, he was the President of the Indian Central Committee to co-operate with the [[Simon Commission]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Gautam Sharma|title=Nationalisation of the Indian Army, 1885\u20131947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=siDiyYi8k74C&pg=PA113|accessdate=11 June 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-7023-555-2|page=113}}</ref> The Committee prepared a well-argued report asking for [[Dominion#India and Pakistan|Dominion Status for India]]. When the Viceregal announcement came granting Dominion Status as the ultimate goal for India, Sir Sankaran Nair retired from active politics. He died in 1934, aged 77.\n\n==Relatives==\nNair's eldest daughter Lady Madhavan Nair and son-in-law and nephew Sir C. Madhavan Nair (a legal luminary and a judge of the Privy Council) lived on a large estate known as Lynwood, in Chennai. Within this property, in the area now known as Lady Madhavan Nair colony/Mahalinagapuram, is situated near the Ayappan-Guruvayoorappan temple, the land for which was donated by Lady Madhavan Nair. There are still many roads bearing names of the house \u2013 Lynwood avenue \u2013 and of the children of Sir and Lady Nair \u2013 Palat Narayani Amma road, Palat Sankaran Nair road, Palat Madhavan Nair road. He also had eight more children, among which another daughter - Saraswathy Amma - was married to the eminent diplomat [[K. P. S. Menon]]. His son [[R. M. Palat]] was also a noted politician by himself.\n\n[[KP Candeth|Lt General Candeth]], a war hero and the liberator of [[Goa]], was another of Sir Sankaran Nair's grandsons.<ref>{{cite book|title=Autobiography of Sir C. Sankaran Nair|url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofs00sirc|year=1966|publisher=Lady Madhavan Nair}}</ref>\n\nHis nephew, [[V.M.M Nair]], is the oldest surviving ICS Officer in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whispersinthecorridors.com/detail/38747-V-M-M-Nair,-India%E2%80%99s-oldest-ICS-officer%E2%80%99s-100th-birthday-on-Oct-8|title=V M M Nair, India\u2019s oldest ICS officer\u2019s 100th birthday on Oct 8 {{!}}{{!}} Whispersinthecorridors|last=|first=|date=|website=www.whispersinthecorridors.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSankaran Nairs  grand-nephew (niece Ammukutty Amma's son) was [[K. K. Chettur]], an [[Indian Civil Service|ICS]] officer who also served as India's first ambassador to Japan. He was the father of [[Jaya Jaitly]], a politician and socialist, whose husband Ashok Jaitly was chief secretary of Jammu and Kashmir. Jaya later had a live in relationship with the Socialist leader and Uninon Minister George Fernandes, which led to a feud between her and Frenandes' legal wife Leila Kabir, at the time of his death. Jaya's  daughter Aditi is married to the former cricketer [[Ajay Jadeja]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* [https://archive.org/details/gandhianarchy00sankuoft ''Gandhi and Anarchy'' (1922)]. Archive.org. Retrieved on 2012-06-11.\n\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nair, C. Sankaran}}\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Indian Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Indian knights]]\n[[Category:Presidency College, Chennai alumni]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Advocates General for Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Members of the Imperial Legislative Council of India]]\n[[Category:Members of the Madras Legislative Council]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sir Chettur Sankaran Nair\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]]\n| image = SirChetturSankaranNair.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1857|07|11}}\n| birth_place = Chettur, [[Kerala]], [[India]]\n| residence = \n| religion = [[Hinduism]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1934|04|24|1857|07|11}}\n| death_place = [[Madras]], [[British India]]\n| office1 = Advocate General of the [[Madras Presidency]]\n| term_start1 = 1906\n| term_end1 = 1908\n| predecessor1 = [[C. A. White]]\n| successor1 = [[P. S. Sivaswami Iyer]]\n| office2 = [[Indian National Congress|President of Indian National Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 1897\n| term_end2 = 1897\n| predecessor2 = [[Rahimtulla M. Sayani]]\n| successor2 = [[Anandamohan Bose]]\n| party = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| profession = Lawyer, jurist, activist, politician\n| footnotes = \n| signature = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Chettur Sankaran Nair''', [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]] (11 July 1857 \u2013 24 April 1934) was the President of the [[Indian National Congress]] in 1897 held at [[Amravati]]. Until present he is the only [[Keralite]] to hold the post.<ref>[http://www.congress.org.in/new/past-president-detail.php?id=11 All India Congress Committee \u2013 AICC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906202647/http://www.congress.org.in/new/past-president-detail.php?id=11 |date=2010-09-06 }}. Congress.org.in. Retrieved on 2012-06-11.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChettur Sankaran Nair was born on 11 July 1857 in Chettur family in [[Mankara]], [[Palakkad District]], as the son of Manmayil Ramunni Panicker and Parvathy Amma Chettur. His early education began in the traditional style at home and continued in schools in Malabar, till he passed the Arts examination with a first class from the Provincial School at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. Then he joined the Presidency College, Madras. In 1877 he took his Arts degree, and two years later secured the Law degree from the Madras Law College.\n\n==Career==\nNair started as a lawyer in 1880 in the High Court of Madras. In 1884, the [[Madras Province|Madras]] Government appointed him as a member of the Committee for an enquiry into the [[Malabar (Northern Kerala)|state of Malabar]]. Till 1908, he was the [[Advocate-General]] to the Government and an Acting Judge from time to time. In 1908, he became a permanent Judge in the High Court of Madras and held the post till 1915. He was a part of the bench that tried [[Collector Ashe]] murder case along with [[C. A. White]], then the Chief Justice of Madras, [[William Ayling (judge)|William Ayling]], as a special case.<ref>[http://madrasmusings.com/Vol%2019%20No%208/The_Ashe_murder_case.html We care for Madras that is Chennai]. Madras Musings (1911-06-17). Retrieved on 2012-06-11.</ref>\n\nIn the meantime, in 1902, the Viceroy [[Lord Curzon]] appointed him Secretary to the [[Raleigh University Commission]]. In recognition of his services, he was appointed a [[Companion of the Indian Empire]] by the King-Emperor in 1904<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/27688/supplements/4010 ''London Gazette'', 21 June 1904]</ref> and in 1912 he was knighted.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/28626/supplements/5082 ''London Gazette'', 12 July 1912]</ref> He became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council|Viceroy's Council]] in 1915 with the charge of the Education portfolio. As member, he wrote in 1919 two famous Minutes of Dissent in the Despatches on Indian Constitutional Reforms, pointing out the various defects of British rule in India and suggesting reforms. For an Indian to offer such criticism and make such demands was incredible in those days. The British government accepted most of his recommendations.Nair resigned from the Viceroy's Council in the aftermath of Jalianwalabagh massacre in April 13,1919,but went to London and joined the Indian Council of States,as a member,remaining in the position till 1925.While there,he wrote the infamous book,''Gandhi and Anarchy'',in 1922,tarnishing the popular image of Mahatma Gandhi.It is the only book he has written.Nair was a vehement critic of Gandhi,as pointed out by Ramachandra Guha,in ''Gandhi:The Years that Changed the World''.Ramachadran,Editor and writer had pointed out in Madhyamam Weekly that Nair had been a British agent.While Rabindra Nath Tagore returned the knighthood after Jalianwala bagh massacre,Nair kept and cherished it.\n\nHe played an active part in the Indian National movement which was gathering force in those days. In 1897, when the First Provincial Conference met in Madras, he was invited to preside over it. The same year, when the [[Indian National Congress]] assembled at [[Amaravathi]], he was chosen its president. In a masterly address, he referred to the highhandedness of foreign administration, called for reforms and asked for self-government for India with Dominion Status. In 1900, he was a member of the [[Madras Legislative Council]]. His official life from 1908 to 1921 interrupted his activities as a free political worker. In 1928, he was the President of the Indian Central Committee to co-operate with the [[Simon Commission]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Gautam Sharma|title=Nationalisation of the Indian Army, 1885\u20131947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=siDiyYi8k74C&pg=PA113|accessdate=11 June 2012|date=1 January 1996|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-7023-555-2|page=113}}</ref> The Committee prepared a well-argued report asking for [[Dominion#India and Pakistan|Dominion Status for India]]. When the Viceregal announcement came granting Dominion Status as the ultimate goal for India, Sir Sankaran Nair retired from active politics. He died in 1934, aged 77.\n\n==Relatives==\nNair's eldest daughter Lady Madhavan Nair and son-in-law and nephew Sir C. Madhavan Nair (a legal luminary and a judge of the Privy Council) lived on a large estate known as Lynwood, in Chennai. Within this property, in the area now known as Lady Madhavan Nair colony/Mahalinagapuram, is situated near the Ayappan-Guruvayoorappan temple, the land for which was donated by Lady Madhavan Nair. There are still many roads bearing names of the house \u2013 Lynwood avenue \u2013 and of the children of Sir and Lady Nair \u2013 Palat Narayani Amma road, Palat Sankaran Nair road, Palat Madhavan Nair road. He also had eight more children, among which another daughter - Saraswathy Amma - was married to the eminent diplomat [[K. P. S. Menon]]. His son [[R. M. Palat]] was also a noted politician by himself.\n\n[[KP Candeth|Lt General Candeth]], a war hero and the liberator of [[Goa]], was another of Sir Sankaran Nair's grandsons.<ref>{{cite book|title=Autobiography of Sir C. Sankaran Nair|url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofs00sirc|year=1966|publisher=Lady Madhavan Nair}}</ref>\n\nHis nephew, [[V.M.M Nair]], is the oldest surving ICS Officer in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whispersinthecorridors.com/detail/38747-V-M-M-Nair,-India%E2%80%99s-oldest-ICS-officer%E2%80%99s-100th-birthday-on-Oct-8|title=V M M Nair, India\u2019s oldest ICS officer\u2019s 100th birthday on Oct 8 {{!}}{{!}} Whispersinthecorridors|last=|first=|date=|website=www.whispersinthecorridors.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSankaran Nairs  grand-nephew (niece Ammukutty Amma's son) was [[K. K. Chettur]], an [[Indian Civil Service|ICS]] officer who also served as India's first ambassador to Japan. He was the father of [[Jaya Jaitly]], a politician and socialist, whose husband Ashok Jaitly was chief secretary of Jammu and Kashmir. Jaya later had a live in relationship with the Socialist leader and Uninon Minister George Fernandes, which led to a feud between her and Frenandes' legal wife Leila Kabir, at the time of his death. Jaya's  daughter Aditi is married to the former cricketer [[Ajay Jadeja]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* [https://archive.org/details/gandhianarchy00sankuoft ''Gandhi and Anarchy'' (1922)]. Archive.org. Retrieved on 2012-06-11.\n\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nair, C. Sankaran}}\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Indian Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Indian knights]]\n[[Category:Presidency College, Chennai alumni]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Advocates General for Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Members of the Imperial Legislative Council of India]]\n[[Category:Members of the Madras Legislative Council]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: surving \u2192 surviving, adjusted spacing near punctuation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._Sankaran_Nair"}
{"title_page": "Peter Navarro", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Economist and member of the Trump administration}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter Navarro\n| image = Peter Navarro official photo.jpg\n| office = Director of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = April 29, 2017\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor =\n| office1 = Director of the [[National Trade Council]]\n| president1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start1 = January 20, 2017\n| term_end1 = April 29, 2017\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1 = Office dissolved\n|birth_name=Peter Kent Navarro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|7|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Peter Kent Navarro''' (born July 15, 1949) is an American economist and author. He serves in the Trump administration as the Assistant to the President, Director of Trade and Manufacturing Policy, and the national [[Defense Production Act]] policy coordinator. He previously served as a Deputy Assistant to the President and Director of the [[White House National Trade Council]], a newly created entity in the [[Executive Branch of the United States|executive branch]] of the U.S. government, until it was folded into the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], a new role established by executive order in April 2017.<ref name=\"joshwapo\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He is also a professor emeritus of [[economics]] and [[public policy]] at the [[Paul Merage School of Business]], [[University of California, Irvine]], and the author of ''[[Death by China]]'', among other publications.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nNavarro's views on trade are significantly outside the mainstream of economic thought, and are widely considered fringe and misguided by other economists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/02/trump-s-cabinet The wonkless White House], ''Economist'' (February 2017): \"Mr Navarro's views on trade are well outside the mainstream, and he is not a big hitter in academic circles.\"</ref><ref name=\"Coy\">Peter Coy, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-08/after-defeating-cohn-trump-s-trade-warrior-is-on-the-rise-again After Defeating Cohn, Trump's Trade Warrior Is on the Rise Again], Bloomberg (March 8, 2018): \"Navarro has come a long way from his roots as a mainstream economist.\"</ref> A strong proponent of reducing [[U.S. trade deficit]]s, Navarro is well known as a critic of Germany and China and has accused both nations of currency manipulation.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lowrey |first1=Annie |title=The 'Madman' Behind Trump's Trade Theory |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/peter-navarro-trump-trade/573913/ |date=December 2018 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He has called for increasing the size of the [[manufacturing in the United States|American manufacturing sector]], setting high tariffs, and \"repatriating global supply chains\". He is also a strong opponent of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nNavarro was born on July 15, 1949, in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/candidates/election.guide/text/CA49.shtml|title=AllPolitics \u2013 Congressional Races \u2013 California District 49|website=www.cnn.com}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{cite magazine |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |title=Peter Navarro Used To Be a Democrat. Now He's the Mastermind Behind Trump's Trade War |url=http://time.com/5375727/peter-navarro/ |date=August 23, 2018 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Navarro's father, Alfred \"Al\" Navarro, a saxophonist and clarinetist, led a [[house band]], which played summers in [[New Hampshire]] and winters in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99097793/|title=Orchestra Leader is Dead from Detroit, Michigan on January 2, 1972 \u00b7 Page 32|newspaper= Detroit Free Press |accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was 9 or 10.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-05-02/trump-s-trade-warrior-is-the-most-unpopular-economist-in-the-class|title=Trump's Trade Warrior Is the Most Unpopular Economist in the Class|date=May 2, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>  Subsequently, he lived with his mother, Evelyn Littlejohn, a [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] secretary, in [[Palm Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-08/local/me-4514_1_peter-navarro|title=Navarro Says Loan for Race Was Inherited: Mayoral candidate admits $300,000 was given to him by his mother, but all the money has been spent|first=Leonard|last=Bernstein|date=August 8, 1992|newspaper=LA Times|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> He lived in [[Bethesda, Maryland]] in a one-bedroom apartment with his mother and brother during his teenage years.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nNavarro went to [[Tufts University]] on a full academic scholarship,<ref name=\":23\" /> graduating in 1972 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He then spent three years in the [[Peace Corps|U.S. Peace Corps]], serving in Thailand.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\"cv\" /> He earned a [[Master of Public Administration]] from [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in 1979, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Economics]] from Harvard under the supervision of [[Richard E. Caves]] in 1986.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web |url=https://merage.uci.edu/_files/documents/faculty-profiles/Navarro-Peter-CV.pdf|title= Peter Navarro Curriculum Vitae |last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=August 2016|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Policy analysis===\nNavarro's policy prescriptions include that \"U.S. should be tough on trade, crack down on intellectual property theft, tax Chinese exports, combat Chinese mercantilism, [and] bring jobs home.\"<ref name=ct />\n\n===Academic career===\nFrom 1981 through 1985, he was a research associate at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]'s Energy and Environmental Policy Center. From 1985 through 1988, he taught at the [[University of California, San Diego]] and the [[University of San Diego]].<ref name = UT>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-peter-navarro-tariffs-san-diego-20180306-htmlstory.html |title=Former San Diego politician Peter Navarro is fighting for Trump's tariffs|last=Hamblin|first=Abby|date=March 6, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> In 1989 he moved to the [[University of California, Irvine]] as a professor of economics and public policy. He continued on the UC Irvine faculty for more than 20 years and is now a professor emeritus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://merage.uci.edu/research-faculty/faculty-directory/Peter-Navarro.html|title=Faculty Directory|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He has worked on energy issues and the relationship between the United States and [[Asia]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|title=Peter Navarro Bio |last=Navarro |first=Peter|website=The Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103004035/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|archivedate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> He has received multiple teaching awards for [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] courses he has taught.<ref name=PMSB-Awards />\n\nAs a doctoral student in 1984, Navarro wrote a book entitled ''The Policy Game: How Special Interests and Ideologues are Stealing America'', which discussed that special interest groups had led the United States to \"a point in its history where it cannot grow and prosper.\" In the book he also called for greater worker's compensation to help those who had lost jobs to trade and foreign competition. His doctoral thesis on why corporations donate to charity is one of his most highly-cited works. He has also done research in the topic of wind energy with Frank Harris, a former student of his.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Publications===\nNavarro is a prolific author with over a dozen books written on various topics in economics and specializing in issues of balance of trade. He has published peer-reviewed economics research on energy policy, charity, deregulation and the economics of trash collection.<ref name=\"ct\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-08-01/peter-navarro-is-the-economist-whose-ideas-guide-trump|title=Here's the Economist Whose Ideas Guide Trump|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|author-link=Tyler Cowen|date=August 1, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Google Scholar Citations |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=usrEMP4AAAAJ&hl=en |website=scholar.google.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Navarro \"is a prolific writer, but has no publications in top-tier academic journals... [although] his research interests are broader than the average economist\u2019s.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/briefing/2017/01/21/peter-navarro-is-about-to-become-one-of-the-worlds-most-powerful-economists|title=Peter Navarro is about to become one of the world's most powerful economists|journal=The Economist|access-date=December 8, 2018|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' is a book published by [[Financial Times|FT Press]] in (2006). Navarro examines China as an emerging [[world power]] confronting challenges at home and abroad as it struggles to exert itself in the [[economic globalization|global market]]. He also discusses how China's role in international commerce is creating conflicts with nations around the world over energy, natural resources, the environment, [[intellectual property]], and other issues. A review in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' describes the book as \"comprehensive\" and \"contemporary\" and concludes that it \"will teach readers to understand the dragon, just not how to vanquish it\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6386391.html?q=The+Coming+China+Wars ''Publishers Weekly review of The Coming China Wars], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', October 30, 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Professor Peter Navarro of the Business School at University of California, Irvine talks his work \"Death by China\" and how China cheats in the world trade system @ University of Michigan-4.jpg|thumb|Professor Peter Navarro discusses his work, ''[[Death by China]]'', arguing China cheats in the world trade system at [[University of Michigan]] in 2012]]\n''[[Death by China]]'' (2011) is a book by Navarro and Greg Autry. According to ''The Economist'', \"the core allegations Mr. Navarro makes against China are not all that controversial. He accuses China of keeping its currency cheap . . . He deplores China\u2019s practice of forcing American firms to hand over intellectual property as a condition of access to its market. He notes, correctly, that Chinese firms pollute the environment more freely and employ workers in far worse conditions than American rules allow.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro argues that China violates fair trade by \"illegal export subsidies and currency manipulation, effectively flooding the U.S. markets\" and unfairly making it \"virtually impossible\" for American companies to compete.<ref name=rs>{{cite web|title=Review: 'Death by China' |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948072?refcatid=31|website=Variety|author=Ronnie Scheib|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> It is a critique of \"global capitalism\" including foreign labor practices and environmental protection.<ref name=\"Salon\">Andrew O'Hehir, [http://www.salon.com/2012/08/22/chinas_not_so_secret_plan_for_world_domination/ \"China\u2019s not-so-secret plan for world domination\"], ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'', August 21, 2012.</ref> Currency manipulation and subsidies are stated as reasons that \"American companies cannot compete because they're not competing with Chinese companies, they're competing with the Chinese government.\"<ref name=ng>[[Neil Genzlinger]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/24/movies/death-by-china-documentary-directed-by-peter-navarro.html \"Casting Blame for Jobs That Vanish\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 23, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Navarro directed and produced a [[documentary film]] based on his book, ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins |first1=Olivera |title=Economist Peter Navarro says U.S. manufacturing is suffering 'Death by China' |url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2012/09/film_says_us_manufacturing_is.html|website=The Cleveland Plain Dealer |accessdate=January 19, 2017|date=September 7, 2012}}</ref> The film, described as \"fervently anti-China\",<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Katie|last=Quan|year=2017|title=Prospects for US-China Union Relations in the Era of Xi and Trump|journal=International Union Rights|page=13|volume=24|issue=4|doi=10.14213/inteuniorigh.24.4.0011 }}</ref> was released under the same title and narrated by [[Martin Sheen]]. From 2011 until 2016, Navarro was a frequent guest on the radio program the John Batchelor Show.\n\n===Political career===\n\n====Politics and campaigns for public office====\nWhile teaching at UC Irvine, Navarro ran unsuccessfully for office in [[San Diego, California]] five times.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name = UT/> In 1992, he [[San Diego mayoral election, 1992|ran for mayor]], finishing first (38.2%) in the primary, but lost with 48% to [[Susan Golding]] in the runoff.<ref name=CSD-M /> During his mayoral campaign, Navarro ran on a no-growth platform.<ref name=\"SanDiegoSprawl\">{{Cite book|title=The Failure of Planning: Permitting Sprawl in San Diego Suburbs, 1970\u20131999|last=Hogan|first=Richard|publisher=[[Ohio State University Press]]|year=2002|isbn=978-0814251041|location=United States|page=[https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119 119]|url=https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119}}</ref> In 1993, he ran for San Diego city council and in 1994 for San Diego County board of supervisors.<ref name = UT/> In 1996, he ran for the [[California's 49th congressional district|49th Congressional District]] as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee, but lost to Republican [[Brian Bilbray]], 52.7% to 41.9%.<ref name=BP-CA49 /> In 2001, Navarro ran in a special election to fill the District 6 San Diego city council seat, but lost in a special election with 7.85% of the vote.<ref name=CSD-CD6 />\n\nNavarro supported President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[phase-out of incandescent light bulbs]], the adoption of [[Wind power|wind energy]], and [[carbon tax]]es in order to stop [[global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/a-pit-bull-for-climate-could-soon-sit-next-to-trump/|title=A \"Pit Bull\" for Climate Could Soon Sit Next to Trump|last=News|first=Robin Bravender,Zack Colman,E&E|work=Scientific American|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Trump campaign advisor ====\nIn 2016, Navarro served as an economic policy adviser to Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"appoint\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/greatagain/navarro-national-trade-council-c2d90c10eacb|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Appoints Dr. Peter Navarro to Head the White House National Trade Council|first=The Transition|last=Team|date=December 21, 2016|website=Medium}}</ref> He advocated for an [[Isolationism|isolationist]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] American foreign policy.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|title=White House At A Crossroads After Cohn|last=Soergel|first=Andrew|date=March 7, 2018|website=US News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308014013/https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Navarro and the international private equity investor [[Wilbur Ross]] authored an economic plan for Trump campaign in September 2016.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan|title=New White Paper on Donald J. Trump's Economic Plan |website=www.donaldjtrump.com|access-date=March 6, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045918/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan |archivedate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Navarro was invited to be an adviser after [[Jared Kushner]], while he was researching China for Trump, saw on Amazon that Navarro co-wrote ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref name=\"Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon\">{{cite web|last1=Vladimirov|first1=Nikita|title=Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/328969-report-kushner-found-trump-economic-advisor-navarro-by-browsing|website=TheHill|accessdate=April 18, 2017|language=English|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> When told that the [[Tax Policy Center]] assessment of Trump's economic plan would reduce federal revenues by $6 trillion and reduce economic growth in the long term, Navarro said that the analysis demonstrated \"a high degree of analytical and political malfeasance\".<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/10/24/trumps-advisers-see-another-conspiracy-far-from-the-campaign-trail/|title=Trump's advisers see another conspiracy \u2013 far from the campaign trail|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> When the Peterson Institute for International Affairs estimated that Trump's economic plan would cost millions of Americans their jobs, Navarro said that writers at the Peterson Institute \"weave a false narrative and they come up with some phony numbers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2016/09/19/trump-adviser-bullish-wake-tax-trade-critiques/ |title=Trump Adviser Bullish in Wake of Tax, Trade Critiques|last=Rainey|first=Ryan|date=September 19, 2016|website=Morning Consult |access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> According to MIT economist [[Simon Johnson (economist)|Simon Johnson]], the economic plan essay authored by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Donald Trump during the campaign had projections \"based on assumptions so unrealistic that they seem to have come from a different planet. If the United States really did adopt Trump's plan, the result would be an immediate and unmitigated disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/trump-insane-economic-plan-by-simon-johnson-2016-09?barrier=accessreg|title=Trump's Magical Economic Thinking|last=Johnson|first=Simon|date=September 30, 2016 |work=Project Syndicate|access-date=March 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When 370 economists, including nineteen Nobel laureates, signed a letter warning against Donald Trump's stated economic policies in November 2016, Navarro said that the letter was \"an embarrassment to the corporate offshoring wing of the economist profession who continues to insist bad trade deals are good for America.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-of-prominent-us-economists-warn-against-voting-trump/|title=Hundreds of US economists warn against voting Trump|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, with [[Wilbur Ross]] and [[Andy Puzder]], Navarro co-authored the essay titled \"Economic Analysis of Donald Trump's Contract with the American Voter\".<ref>[[Wilbur Ross]], [[Andy Puzder]] & Peter Navarro, [http://www.publicnow.com/view/26F924AB8FA783A28FEA3EE8943635B4F0574556?2016-10-31-14:32:09+00:00-xxx4035]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald J. Trump for President, Inc.]], October 30, 2016</ref>\n\n====White House trade advisor====\n[[File:Peter Navarro, Director of the White House National Trade Council, Addresses in the Oval Office before U.S. President Donald Trump Signs Executive Orders Regarding Trade on March 31, 2017 4.jpg|thumb|Director Peter Navarro addresses President [[Donald Trump]]'s promises to American people, workers, and domestic manufacturers ('''[https://assets.donaldjtrump.com/DJT_DeclaringAmericanEconomicIndependence.pdf Declaring American Economic Independence]''' on June 28, 2016) in the [[Oval Office]] with [[U.S. Vice President|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] and [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Wilbur Ross]] before President Trump signs [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Orders]] regarding trade in March 2017<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-regarding-omnibus-report-significant-trade Presidential Executive Order Regarding the Omnibus Report on Significant Trade Deficits], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-establishing-enhanced-collection-and Presidential Executive Order on Establishing Enhanced Collection and Enforcement of Antidumping and Countervailing Duties and Violations of Trade and Customs Laws], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref>]]\nOn December 21, 2016, Navarro was selected by President-elect Trump to head a newly created position, as director of the [[White House National Trade Council]].<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title='Death by China' author to lead Trump trade office|url=https://www.ft.com/content/71a201d2-c7b3-11e6-8f29-9445cac8966f|website=www.ft.com|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> He outlines President Trump's trade policy as aiming to create jobs, revive the manufacturing sector, and improve the country's trade balance. He warned that trade deficits could jeopardize U.S. national security by allowing unfriendly nations to encroach on American supply chains. One of his main missions is to focus on behaviors by other countries that he considers abusive, cheating, illegal, and unfair against the U.S.<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4659659/peter-navarro-outlines-trump-administration-trade-policy-priorities Peter Navarro Outlines Trump Administration Trade Policy Priorities], [[C-SPAN]], June 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/videos/2017-03-31/navarro-says-not-all-trade-deficits-necessarily-bad-video Peter Navarro Says Trade Deficits Aren't Always Bad], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], March 31, 2017</ref>\n\n====Director of Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy====\nIn April 2017, the National Trade Council became part of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], of which Navarro was appointed Director.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news| last1=Cook | first1=Nancy | last2=Restuccia | first2=Andrew |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/peter-navarro-trump-trade-240611|title=Trump's trade warrior prowls the West Wing|date=July 17, 2017|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> By September 2017, the Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy had been folded into the National Economic Council, which meant that Navarro would report to NEC Director [[Gary Cohn (investment banker)|Gary Cohn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/27/peter-navarro-trade-office-national-economic-council-243217|title=Kelly folds Navarro's trade shop into National Economic Council|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, several media outlets reported that Navarro's influence in the administration was rising again and that he would likely be promoted from the secondary billet of Deputy Assistant to the President to Assistant to the President, giving Navarro parity with the NEC Director.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Swanson | first1=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, a Top Trade Skeptic, Is Ascendant | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/25/us/politics/peter-navarro-trade.html | date=February 25, 2018 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Lynch | first1=David J. | last2=Damian | first2=Paletta | title=Trump Tilts Toward Hard-Liners Ahead of Key Trade Decisions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/trump-tilts-toward-hard-liners-ahead-of-key-trade-decisions/2018/02/26/ffe93e46-1b32-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html | date=February 26, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Josh Rogin]], writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', reported that Navarro had used his prior time of lower influence to lead several low-profile policy items, such as working to increase military funding, drafting [[:s:Executive Order 13806|Executive Order 13806]], and leading the effort to solve a dispute between the United States and [[Qatar]] over the Open Skies Agreement between the two countries.<ref name=\"joshwapo\">{{cite news | last1=Rogin | first1=Josh | title=How Peter Navarro Got His Groove Back | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2018/02/27/how-peter-navarro-got-his-groove-back/ | date=February 27, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn explaining his role in the Trump administration, Navarro said that he is there to \"provide the underlying analytics that confirm [Trump's] intuition [on trade]. And his intuition is always right in these matters.\"<ref name=\"Coy\" />\n\nIn June 2018, Navarro said that there was \"a special place in hell\" for Justin Trudeau, the Prime Minister of Canada, after Trudeau said that Canada would respond with retaliatory tariffs since the United States had placed tariffs on Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/10/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Peter Navarro says 'there's a special place in hell' for Justin Trudeau|last= Watkins|first=Eli|work=CNN|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> The Prime Minister's point-of-view and Canada's response to these tariffs were already public and well-known when Navarro made this comment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/white-house-adviser-kudlow-trump-trudeau-g7-summit-blame-1.4700061|title='Special place in hell': Trump advisers blast Trudeau for comments at G7 summit {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>  Navarro later apologized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/12/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Navarro sorry after saying there's a 'special place in hell' for Trudeau|first=Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Navarro said that Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States as \"a brilliant move\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/31/mnuchin-and-lighthizer-were-opposed-to-trump-tariffs-on-mexico-source-says.html|title=Mnuchin and Lighthizer opposed Trump tariffs on Mexico, source says|last=Higgins|first=Kayla Tausche,Tucker|date=May 31, 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, after being tasked by the President to combat China's usage of international mail rates to more cheaply ship products into the US, Navarro successfully led a diplomatic effort to the third Extraordinary Congress of the [[Universal Postal Union]] where it agreed member countries could be able to opt-in to self-declare their rates starting in July 2020, after repeated threats from the Trump administration to leave the UPU unless global postage rates were changed so countries like China could no longer unfairly benefit from international delivery prices, particularly when it came to e-commerce deliveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/26/trump-scores-a-big-victory-on-stamps-postal-union-terminal-dues-china/|title=Trump Scores a Big Victory-on Stamps|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-un-postal/u-n-postal-union-clinches-deal-to-keep-u-s-in-club-idUSKBN1WA247|title=U.N. postal union clinches deal to keep U.S. in club|last= Nebehay|first=Stephanie|work=Reuters|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavarro continued to promote policies challenging amid trade negotiations between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Schlesinger | first1=Jacob M. | last2=Salama | first2=Vivian | title=New White House Report, Authored by Trade Hawk, Blasts Chinese 'Economic Aggression'  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-white-house-report-authored-by-trade-hawk-blasts-chinese-economic-aggression-1529456401 | date=June 19, 2018 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=In the Battles Over Trump's Trade Wars, Hawkish Adviser Navarro Endures  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-the-battles-over-trumps-trade-wars-hawkish-adviser-navarro-endures-11576943074 | date=December 21, 2019 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Rappeport | first1=Alan | last2=Swanson | first2=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, Trump's Trade Warrior, Has Not Made His Peace With China | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/26/us/politics/peter-navarro-china-trade.html | date=December 26, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro worked with the DHS to initiate a crackdown on counterfeited and pirated e-commerce goods from overseas,<ref>{{cite web | last1=Shepardson | first1=David | title=U.S. to unveil crackdown on counterfeit, pirated e-commerce goods | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-counterfeiting/u-s-to-unveil-crackdown-on-counterfeit-pirated-e-commerce-goods-idUSKBN1ZN02E | date=January 23, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/us/politics/us-cracks-down-on-counterfeits-in-a-warning-shot-to-china.html |title=U.S. Cracks Down on Counterfeits in a Warning Shot to China - The New York Times |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= January 24, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mauldin | first1=William | last2=Leary | first2=Alex | title=U.S. Signals Crackdown on Counterfeit Goods Sold Online  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-signals-crackdown-on-counterfeit-goods-sold-online-11579820400 | date=January 24, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/24/dhs-report-targets-online-counterfeit-sales-on-amazon-e-commerce.html |title=DHS report targets online counterfeit sales on Amazon, e-commerce |publisher=Cnbc.com |date= |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref> and he promoted the administration's actions on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jessica Bursztynsky |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/16/navarro-to-amazon-ebay-china-trade-deal-cracks-down-on-counterfeits.html |title=Navarro to Amazon, eBay: China trade deal cracks down on counterfeits |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=January 16, 2020 |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Peter |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/perspectives/peter-navarro-e-commerce-counterfeit-products/index.html |title=Navarro: Counterfeits harm Americans and threaten national security. Trump has a plan to combat them (opinion) |publisher=CNN |date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Trump signed an executive order on the matter on January 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web | title=Trump signs executive order aimed at preventing sales of counterfeit goods from overseas | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-shipments/trump-signs-executive-order-aimed-at-preventing-sales-of-counterfeit-goods-from-overseas-idUSKBN1ZU35P | date=January 31, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, it was reported that Navarro was conducting his own investigation into the identity of the author of [[I Am Part of the Resistance Inside the Trump Administration|an anonymous op-ed in ''The New York Times'']] criticizing the Trump Administration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Suebsaeng | first1=Asawin | last2=Markay | first2=Lachlan | title=Trump's Top Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Has a Side Project: Secretly Hunting for 'Anonymous' | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-top-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-has-a-side-project-secretly-hunting-for-anonymous | date=February 17, 2020 | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Infrastructure plan====\nDuring the campaign Navarro, together with [[Wilbur Ross]] who became Trump's [[Commerce Secretary]], designed a $1 trillion infrastructure development plan for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name=\"peternavarro.com\">{{cite web|url=http://peternavarro.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/infrastructurereport.pdf|title=Infrastructure report|date=|publisher=peternavarro.com|accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref> The plan called for $137 billion in tax credits to private business to induce them to financing the bulk of infrastructure spending. Economists across the political spectrum derided the proposal.<ref name=\"Mufson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/economists-pan-infrastructure-plan-championed-by-trump-nominees/2017/01/17/0ed1ad5e-dc5e-11e6-918c-99ede3c8cafa_story.html|title=Economists pan infrastructure plan championed by Trump nominees|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=January 17, 2017|via=www.washingtonpost.com|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> Trump released a $1.5 trillion version of this plan in February 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/infrastructure/373408-white-house-releases-55-page-infrastructure-proposal|title=White House releases 55-page, $1.5 trillion infrastructure plan|first=Mallory|last=Shelbourne|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> but the Republican-controlled Congress showed little enthusiasm for the proposal, with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] reporting, \"President Trump's infrastructure plan appears to have crashed and burned in Congress\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/377681-trumps-infrastructure-push-hits-wall-in-congress|title=Trump's infrastructure push hits wall in Congress|first=Dustin|last=Weaver|date=March 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Coronavirus pandemic====\nOn January 29, 2020, Navarro issued a memo warning that [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]] could \"evolv[e] into a full-blown pandemic, imperiling the lives of millions of Americans\" and that the \"risk of a worst-case pandemic scenario should not be overlooked\". He argued for restrictions on travel from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trade Adviser Warned White House in January of Risks of a Pandemic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/us/politics/navarro-warning-trump-coronavirus.html |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Klar | first1=Rebecca | title=Trump adviser warned of coronavirus threat in January | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/491490-trump-adviser-warned-of-coronavirus-threat-in-january | date=April 7, 2020 | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Navarro wrote another memo on February 23, 2020, arguing that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] \"could infect as many as 100 million Americans, with a loss of life of as many as 1-2 million souls\" and calling for an \"immediate supplemental appropriation of at least $3 billion.\"<ref>{{cite web | last1=Swan | first1=Jonathan | last2=Talev | first2=Margaret | title=Navarro memos warning of mass coronavirus death circulated in January | url=https://www.axios.com/exclusive-navarro-deaths-coronavirus-memos-january-da3f08fb-dce1-4f69-89b5-ea048f8382a9.html | date=April 7, 2020 | work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] | accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> At the same time that Navarro was issuing warnings, he said in public that the American people had \"nothing to worry about\" regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/politics/peter-navarro-coronavirus/index.html|title=Navarro publicly said Americans had 'nothing to worry about' while privately warning coronavirus could cost lives and dollars|author1=Em Steck |author2=Andrew Kaczynski|website=CNN|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, Trump appointed Navarro to coordinate the federal government's [[Defense Production Act]] policy response during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489938-trump-names-new-defense-production-act-coordinator-for-coronavirus|title=Trump names new Defense Production Act coordinator for coronavirus fight|first=Morgan|last=Chalfant|date=March 27, 2020|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Pappas | first1=Alex | title=Trump appoints Navarro to lead Defense Production Act efforts after forcing GM to make ventilators | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-aide-navarro-lead-defense-production-act-efforts | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=\u2018This is War\u2019: President\u2019s Equipment Czar to Use Full Powers to Fight Coronavirus | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-is-war-presidents-equipment-czar-to-use-full-powers-to-fight-coronavirus-11585435836 | date=March 28, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro clashed with [[Anthony Fauci]], the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]], over whether the administration should promote the use of [[hydroxychloroquine]] to treat the virus despite being unproven.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-hydroxychloroquine-white-house-01306286-0bbc-4042-9bfe-890413c6220d.html|title=Inside the epic White House blowup over \"game-changer\" hydroxychloroquine|last=Swan|first=Jonathan|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views on trade ==\n{{main|International trade|Commercial policy|Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign}}\nNavarro has been a staunch critic of trade with China and strong proponent of reducing U.S. trade deficits. He has attacked Germany, Japan and China for currency manipulation. He has called for increasing the size of the American manufacturing sector, setting high tariffs, and repatriating global supply chains. He was a fierce opponent of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\nAccording to [[Bloomberg News]], Navarro had \"roots as a mainstream economist\" as he voiced support for free trade in his 1984 book ''The Policy Game''. He changed his positions as he saw \"the globalist erosion of the American economy\" develop.<ref name=\"Coy\"/>\n\nAccording to ''Politico'', Navarro's economic theories are \"considered fringe\" by his fellow economists.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2017/03/trump-trade-attack-dog-peter-navarro-000353|title=Trump's attack dog on trade|last=|first=|date=|work=The Agenda|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> A ''New Yorker'' reporter described Navarro's views on trade and China as so radical \"that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/trumps-muse-on-u-s-trade-with-china|title=Trump's Muse on U.S. Trade with China|last=|first=|date=October 12, 2016|website=The New Yorker|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's views on trade and China are so radical, however, that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.}}</ref> The ''Economist'' described Navarro as having \"oddball views\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21721937-donald-trumps-economic-strategy-unimaginative-and-incoherent-cooking-up-economic-policy|title=Cooking up an economic policy|website=The Economist|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> The George Mason University economist [[Tyler Cowen]] has described him as \"one of the most versatile and productive American economists of the last few decades\", but Cowen noted that he disagreed with his views on trade, which he claimed go \"against a strong professional consensus.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> University of Michigan economist [[Justin Wolfers]] described Navarro's views as \"far outside the mainstream,\" noting that \"he endorses few of the key tenets of\" the economics profession.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/upshot/why-most-economists-are-so-worried-about-trump.html|title=Why Most Economists Are So Worried About Trump|last=Wolfers|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|access-date=January 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331|quote=the only official who identifies as an economist\u2014Peter Navarro, who earned a Harvard Ph.D. in economics and will head up the newly formed National Trade Council\u2014stands so far outside the mainstream that he endorses few of the key tenets of the profession.|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> According to Lee Branstetter, economics professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University|Carnegie Mellon]] and trade expert with the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], Navarro \"was never a part of the group of economists who ever studied the global free-trade system ... He doesn't publish in journals. What he's writing and saying right now has nothing to do with what he got his Harvard Ph.D. in ... he doesn't do research that would meet the scientific standards of that community.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://businessinsider.com/what-is-trumpenomics-according-to-peter-navarro-2017-1|title=The clearest articulation of what Trump wants to do to America's economy comes from one person|last=|first=|date=|work=Business Insider|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Marcus Noland, an economist at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, described a tax and trade paper written by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Trump as \"a complete misunderstanding of international trade, on their part.\"<ref name=\":82\"/>\n\nIn August 2019, Navarro asserted the tariffs of the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]] were not hurting Americans. Citing extensive evidence to the contrary, Politifact rated Navarro's assertion \"Pants on Fire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/aug/20/peter-navarro/donald-trumps-tariffs-china-dont-hurt-americans-to/|title=Tariffs on China don't hurt Americans? Pants on Fire|website=@politifact}}</ref>\n\n=== Border adjustment tax ===\nNavarro supports a tax policy called \"border adjustment\", which, as commonly used in the [[value added taxes|VATs]] of most countries, taxes all imports at the domestic rate while rebating tax on exports, essentially transforming taxes from taxes on production to taxes on consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to criticism that the border adjustment tax could hurt U.S. companies and put jobs at risk, Navarro called it \"fake news.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Criticism of China ===\nAccording to ''Politico'', \"Navarro is perhaps the most extreme advocate in Washington, and maybe in all of economics, for an aggressive stance toward China.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Navarro put his attention to China in the mid-2000s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/13/peter-navarro-profile-national-trade-council-donald-trump-china-expert/ |title=Trump's Top China Expert Isn't a China Expert|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> His first publication on the subject is the 2006 book ''[[The Coming China Wars: Where They Will Be Fought, How They Can Be Won]]''.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/peter-navarro-trump-trade-china-214772 |title=The Most Dangerous Man in Trump World?|work=Politico|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Navarro has said that he started to examine China when he noticed that his former students were losing jobs, concluding that China was at fault.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn ''Politico''{{'}}s description of the book, \"Navarro uses military language to refer to China's trade policies, referring to its 'conquest' of the world's export markets, which has 'vaporized literally millions of manufacturing jobs and driven down wages.' ... China's aspirations are so insatiable, he claims, that eventually there will be a clash over \"our most basic of all needs\u2014bread, water, and air.'\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Navarro has described the entry of China to the World Trade Organization as one of the United States' biggest mistakes.<ref name=\":8\" /> To respond to the Chinese threat, Navarro has advocated for 43% tariffs, the repudiation of trade pacts, major increases in military expenditures and strengthened military ties with Taiwan.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"a wide range of economists have warned that curtailing trade with China would damage the American economy, forcing consumers to pay higher prices for goods and services.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/21/us/politics/peter-navarro-carl-icahn-trump-china-trade.html|title=Trump Taps Peter Navarro, Vocal Critic of China, for New Trade Post|last=Appelbaum|first=Binyamin|date=December 21, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Navarro has reportedly also encouraged President Trump to enact a 25-percent tariff on Chinese steel imports, something that \"trade experts worry... would upend global trade practices and cause countries to retaliate, potentially leading to a trade war\".<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\nNavarro has said that a large part of China's competitive advantage over the United States stems from unfair trade practices.<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro has criticized China for pollution, poor labor standards, government subsidies, producing \"contaminated, defective and cancerous\" exports, currency manipulation, and theft of US intellectual property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-06/u-s-aims-to-reclaim-global-supply-chain-trump-trade-aide-says|title=U.S. Will Reclaim Global Supply Chain, Trump Trade Aide Says|date=March 6, 2017|publisher=Bloomberg|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In his 2012 documentary, Navarro said that China caused the loss of 57,000 US factories and 25 million jobs. Navarro maintains that China manipulates its currency, and although most economists believe that it is not the case, the U.S. Treasury officially designated China as a \"Currency Manipulator\" on August 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm751|title=Treasury Designates China as a Currency Manipulator {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOf the more than dozen China specialists contacted by ''Foreign Policy'', most either did not know of him or only interacted with him briefly.<ref name=\":8\" /> Kenneth Pomeranz, University of Chicago professor of Chinese History, said that his \"recollection is that [Navarro] generally avoided people who actually knew something about the country.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> Columnist [[Gordon G. Chang]] was the only China watcher contacted by ''Foreign Policy'' who defended Navarro, but even then noted that he disagreed with Navarro's claims of currency manipulation, opposition to the TPP and calls for high tariffs.<ref name=\":8\" /> James McGregor, a former chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in China, said that Navarro's books and documentary on China \"have close to zero credibility with people who know the country,\" and are filled with \"hyperbole, inaccuracies\" and a \"cartoonish caricature of China that he puts out.\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nSome of Navarro's views on China fit within the mainstream, such as criticism of Chinese currency manipulation (pre-2015), concern that China\u2019s rapid ascension to the World Trade Organization harmed the Rust Belt, and criticism of China's weak environmental regulations and poor labor standards.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Ron Vara ===\nIn six of his books about China, Navarro quotes a \"Ron Vara\", whom he describes as a China hawk and former Harvard PhD doctoral student in economics, and who says crass Sinophobic things about China and the Chinese. An investigation by the ''Chronicle'' found that this [[Author surrogate|character]] was made up, and that Ron Vara (an anagram of Navarro) appeared to represent views that Navarro himself held.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/20191015-navarro|title=Trump's 'China Muse' Has an Imaginary Friend|date=October 15, 2019|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horsley |first1=Scott |title=White House Adviser Peter Navarro Calls Fictional Alter Ego An 'Inside Joke' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/18/771396016/white-house-adviser-peter-navarro-calls-fictional-alter-ego-an-inside-joke |website=npr |publisher=National Public Radio |accessdate=October 19, 2019 |quote=\"As she put it, the joke wears very thin when you get to certain statements about China and the Chinese people that are quite negative,\" Bartlett said. \"Ron Vara says things that are pretty over the top, and it's hard to construe them necessarily as whimsical in the way we normally use that word.\"}}</ref> Navarro has admitted to making up the character and quoting him in his books. Economist [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]], who co-authored ''Seeds of Destruction'' with Navarro,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crook |first1=Clive |title=Hubbard and Navarro on the 'Seeds of Destruction' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2010/11/hubbard-and-navarro-on-the-seeds-of-destruction/66167/ |website=The Atlantic |publisher=The Atlantic |accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref> has said he was not aware that Vara was fictional and that he was not okay with it. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Arciga |first1=Julia |title=Trump Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Admits to Quoting Character He Invented in His Books |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-admits-to-quoting-character-he-invented-in-his-books |website=Daily Beast |accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, a memo apparently authored by Ron Vara began circulating in Washington DC. The memo highlighted the \"Keep Tariff Argument\" and the use of tariffs against China a few days before an additional 15% tariff on $160 billion of Chinese made goods was set to be implemented. Navarro later confirmed that he had written the memo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/11/peter-navarros-alter-ego-ron-vara-shares-pro-tariff-memo-amid-trade-talks.html|title=Peter Navarro's alter ego 'Ron Vara' shares pro-tariff memo amid US-China trade talks|author=|date=December 11, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\nNavarro drew controversy when he accused Germany of using a \"grossly undervalued\" euro to \"exploit\" the US and the rest of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/57f104d2-e742-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> ''Politico'' noted that the German government does not set the value of the euro.<ref name=\":7\" /> Economists and commentators are divided on the accuracy of Navarro's remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2017/02/is-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=Is Germany a currency manipulator? |publisher=Bruegel|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/485bace6-ea0a-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said that Navarro was right and wrong at the same time: \"Yes, Germany in effect has an undervalued currency relative to what it would have without the euro... But does this mean that the euro as a whole is undervalued against the dollar? Probably not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/02/01/germany-the-euro-and-currency-manipulation/|title=Germany, the Euro, and Currency Manipulation|website=Paul Krugman Blog|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Boston University economist [[Laurence Kotlikoff]] described Navarro's accusation of Germany as a currency manipulator as \"#stupideconomics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kotlikoff/2017/02/01/the-latest-stupideconomics-peter-navarro-calls-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=The Latest #StupidEconomics \u2013 Peter Navarro Calls Germany A 'Currency Manipulator'|last=Kotlikoff|first=Laurence|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nNavarro argues that the decline in US manufacturing jobs is chiefly due to \"unfair trade practices and bad trade deals. And if you don't believe that, just go to the booming factories in Germany, in Japan, in Korea, in China, in Malaysia, in Vietnam, in Indonesia, in Italy\u2014every place that we're running deficits with.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/03/526621048/peter-navarro-a-bricklayer-of-trumps-protectionist-wall|title=Peter Navarro: A 'Bricklayer' Of Trump's Protectionist Wall |publisher=NPR|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> However, many economists attribute the decline in manufacturing jobs chiefly to [[automation]] and other innovations that allow manufacturing firms to produce more goods with fewer workers, rather than trade.<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/27/news/economy/donald-trump-economy/index.html|title=Trump will grow the economy like Reagan, says adviser Peter Navarro|last=Long|first=Heather|date=June 27, 2016|website=CNN Money|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNavarro has been a proponent of strengthening the manufacturing sector's role in the national economy: \"We envision a more Germany-style economy, where 20 percent of our workforce is in manufacturing. ... And we're not talking about banging tin in the back room.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"experts on manufacturing ... doubt that the government can significantly increase factory employment, noting that mechanization is the major reason fewer people are working in factories.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Opposition to NAFTA ===\nNavarro has called for the United States to leave the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and has tried to convince President Trump to initiate a withdrawal.<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\n=== Repatriation of global supply chains ===\nNavarro has called for repatriating global supply chains.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> According to ''Politico'''s [[Jacob Heilbrunn]], such a move \"would be enormously costly and take years to execute\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Trade as a national security risk ===\nNavarro has framed trade as a national security risk.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-makes-cutting-trade-deficit-top-priority-1488815842|title=Trump Adviser Peter Navarro: Trade Deficits Endanger U.S. National Security|last=Timiraos|first=Nick|date=March 6, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nNavarro has characterized foreign purchases of U.S. companies as a threat to national security, but according to NPR, this is \"a fringe view that puts him at odds with the vast majority of economists.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/03/10/519488848/trump-advisers-warning-about-food-supply-takeover-met-with-skepticism|title=Trump Adviser's Warning About Food Supply Takeover Met With Skepticism|last=|first=|date=|work=NPR.org|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en|quote=Peter Navarro says foreign companies buying up U.S. corporations are posing a threat to national security.}}</ref> Dartmouth economist Douglas Irwin noted that the US government already reviews foreign purchases of companies with military or strategic value, and has on occasion rejected such deals.<ref name=\":2\" /> Irwin said that Navarro had not substantiated his claim with any evidence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro has also said that the United States has \"already begun to lose control of [its] food supply chain\", which according to NPR, \"sounded pretty off-the-wall to a number of economists\" who noted that the US is a massive exporter of food.<ref name=\":2\" /> Dermot Hayes, an agribusiness economist at Iowa State University, described Navarro's statement as \"uninformed\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro criticized the [[outsourcing]] of critical materials \u2014 like the production of essential [[Medical device|medical supplies]] \u2014 to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade deficits ===\n{{main|Balance of trade}}\nNavarro is a proponent of the notion that [[trade deficit]]s are bad in and of themselves, a view which is widely rejected by trade experts and economists.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/06/economists-take-aim-at-trump-trade-theory-again-peter-navarro-bilateral-multilateral-trade-deals-china-germany-national-security/ |title=Economists Take Aim at Trump Trade Theory \u2013 Again |first=Robbie |last=Gramer |website=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's comments drew skepticism from trade experts and economists across the political spectrum\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro and Ross say that getting rid of the trade deficit and boosting investment would also spur faster economic growth, which would bring in $1.74 trillion in tax revenue over a decade.\"}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/03/07/trump-rails-against-the-trade-deficit-but-economists-say-theres-no-easy-way-for-him-to-make-it-go-away/|title=Analysis {{!}} Trump rails against trade deficit, but economists say there's no easy way for him to make it go away|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In a white paper co-authored with Wilbur Ross, Navarro stated, \"when a country runs a trade deficit by importing more than it exports, this subtracts from growth.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/navarros-trade-views-misguided-dangerous|title=Navarro's Trade Views 'Misguided', 'Dangerous'|date=December 23, 2016|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref> In a ''Wall Street Journal'' op-ed defending his views, Navarro stated, \"If we are able to reduce our trade deficits through tough, smart negotiations, we should be able to increase our growth.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-white-house-worries-about-trade-deficits-1488751930|title=Why the White House Worries About Trade Deficits|last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=March 5, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Harvard University economics professor [[Greg Mankiw|Gregory Mankiw]] has said that Navarro's views on the trade deficit are based on the kind of mistakes that \"even a freshman at the end of ec 10 knows.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2016/09/trumponomics.html|title=Greg Mankiw's Blog: Trumponomics|last=|first=|date=|website=gregmankiw.blogspot.com|language=en|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> Tufts University professor [[Daniel W. Drezner]] said about Navarro's op-ed, \"as someone who's written on this topic I could not for the life of me understand his reasoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2017/03/09/why-the-trump-administration-hates-multilateral-trade-agreements-the-most/|title=Perspective {{!}} Why the Trump administration hates multilateral trade agreements the most|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> According to [[Tyler Cowen]], \"close to no one\" in the economics profession agrees with Navarro's idea that a trade deficit is bad in and of itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208134200/http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archivedate=December 8, 2016|title=What You Should Know About the Professor Who Has Trump's Ear on the Economy |publisher= The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 8, 2016|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> Nobel laureate [[Angus Deaton]] described Navarro's attitude on trade deficits as \"an old-fashioned mercantilist position.\"<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' magazine has described Navarro's views on the trade deficit as \"dodgy economics\",<ref name=\":0\" /> while the ''Financial Times'' has described them as \"poor economics\".<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eea50292-0331-11e7-aa5b-6bb07f5c8e12|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Economists Noah Smith,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-12-28/trump-s-trade-chief-peter-navarro-makes-a-rookie-mistake|title=Trump's Trade Chief Makes a Rookie Mistake|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=December 28, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Sumner]], [[Olivier Blanchard]],<ref name=\":10\" /> and Phil Levy<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/phillevy/2017/03/06/white-house-whiffs-on-trade-deficit-defense/#7aea21f06b6c|title=White House Whiffs On Trade Deficit Defense|last=Levy |first=Phil|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> have also criticized Navarro's views on the trade deficit. Dan Ikenson, director of the [[Cato Institute]]'s Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies goes so far as to call Navarro a \"charlatan\" and says that \"99.9 per cent of respectable economists would eschew\" what he says: \"He says imports deduct from output, and he calls that accounting identity the 'economic growth formula'. He thinks that for every dollar we import, our GDP is reduced by a dollar. I don't know how he got his PhD at Harvard.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=The purge of April: Trump's new advisers pour on the gas |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/the-purge-of-april-trump-s-new-advisers-pour-on-the-gas-1.4705201 |website=www.cbc.ca |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to Trans-Pacific Partnership ===\nNavarro opposes the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/238473-parsing-the-trans-pacific-partnership-agreement|title=Parsing the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=April 13, 2015|work=The Hill|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In an April 2015 op-ed, Navarro said, \"To woo us, their spinmeisters boast the TPP will spur American exports to stimulate sorely needed economic growth. In truth, the American economy will suffer severely. This is because the TPP will hammer two main drivers of economic growth\u2014domestic investment and 'net exports.'\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Navarro said in March 2017 that TPP \"would have been a \"death knell\" to America's auto and vehicle parts industry that we \"urgently need to bring back to full life.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> ''Politico''<nowiki/>'s Jacob Heilbrunn and ''the'' ''Economist'' argue that there may be a disconnect between Navarro's policy on China and his opposition to the TPP, as scuttling the TPP will strengthen China's hand.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Library resources box|about=no|by=yes}}\n\n* ''Crouching Tiger: What China's Militarism Means for the World'' (2015)\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBe2wpZqN0s Episode 1: Will There Be War With China?]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUA_wh88fYc Episode 2: The World At the Tip of a Chinese Spear]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odiv79hZhB4 Episode 3: The Wild Card of North Korea]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HEjlcmfNt3Y Episode 4: The Unsinkable Aircraft Carrier of Taiwan]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1csrTOxJ8JM Episode 5: Will There Be War Between China and Japan?]\n* ''[[Death by China (book)|Death by China: Confronting the Dragon \u2013 A Global Call to Action]]'' (2011)\n* ''Seeds of Destruction'' (with [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]]) (2010)\n* ''Always a Winner: Finding Your Competitive Advantage in an Up and Down Economy'' (2009)\n* ''The Well-Timed Strategy: Managing the Business Cycle for Competitive Advantage'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' (2006)\n* ''What the Best MBAs Know'' (2005)\n* ''Principles of Economics: Business, Banking, Finance, and Your Everyday Life'' (2005)\n* ''When the Market Moves, Will You Be Ready?'' (2003)\n* ''If It's Raining in Brazil, Buy Starbucks''<ref name=ISBN /> (2001)\n* ''Bill Clinton's Agenda for America'' (1993)\n* ''Job Opportunities Under Clinton/Gore'' (with Craig Adams) (1993)\n* ''The Policy Game'' (1984)\n* ''The Dimming of America: The Real Costs of Electric Utility Regulation'' (1984)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"PMSB-Awards\">{{cite web|title=Teaching Awards|url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|publisher=The Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826230801/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|archivedate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BP-CA49\">{{cite web|title=California's 49th Congressional District Elections|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California%27s_49th_Congressional_District|publisher=Ballotpedia|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-M\">{{cite web|title=Election Results \u2013 Mayor, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/mayorresults.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-CD6\">{{cite web|title=Election History \u2013 Council District 6, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/cd6results.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ISBN\">{{cite web|title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Books|url=http://www.isbnsearch.org/search?s=peter+navarro|publisher=ISBN Search|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Peter Navarro}}\n* [http://www.peternavarro.com/ Official site]\n* {{C-SPAN|Peter Navarro 02}}\n* [http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589 UCI Faculty Profile]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2304583/ Death by China] at [[IMDb]]\n\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Navarro, Peter}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American economics writers]]\n[[Category:Economists from California]]\n[[Category:Economists from Florida]]\n[[Category:Economists from Maryland]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Peace Corps volunteers]]\n[[Category:People from Bethesda, Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Irvine faculty]]\n[[Category:Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Economist and member of the Trump administration}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter Navarro\n| image = Peter Navarro official photo.jpg\n| office = Director of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = April 29, 2017\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor =\n| office1 = Director of the [[National Trade Council]]\n| president1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start1 = January 20, 2017\n| term_end1 = April 29, 2017\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1 = Office dissolved\n|birth_name=Peter Kent Navarro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|7|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Peter Kent Navarro''' (born July 15, 1949) is an American economist and author. He serves in the Trump administration as the Assistant to the President, Director of Trade and Manufacturing Policy, and the national [[Defense Production Act]] policy coordinator. He previously served as a Deputy Assistant to the President and Director of the [[White House National Trade Council]], a newly created entity in the [[Executive Branch of the United States|executive branch]] of the U.S. government, until it was folded into the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], a new role established by executive order in April 2017.<ref name=\"joshwapo\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He is also a professor emeritus of [[economics]] and [[public policy]] at the [[Paul Merage School of Business]], [[University of California, Irvine]], and the author of ''[[Death by China]]'', among other publications.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nNavarro's views on trade are significantly outside the mainstream of economic thought, and are widely considered fringe and misguided by other economists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/02/trump-s-cabinet The wonkless White House], ''Economist'' (February 2017): \"Mr Navarro's views on trade are well outside the mainstream, and he is not a big hitter in academic circles.\"</ref><ref name=\"Coy\">Peter Coy, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-08/after-defeating-cohn-trump-s-trade-warrior-is-on-the-rise-again After Defeating Cohn, Trump's Trade Warrior Is on the Rise Again], Bloomberg (March 8, 2018): \"Navarro has come a long way from his roots as a mainstream economist.\"</ref> A strong proponent of reducing [[U.S. trade deficit]]s, Navarro is well known as a critic of Germany and China and has accused both nations of currency manipulation.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lowrey |first1=Annie |title=The 'Madman' Behind Trump's Trade Theory |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/peter-navarro-trump-trade/573913/ |date=December 2018 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He has called for increasing the size of the [[manufacturing in the United States|American manufacturing sector]], setting high tariffs, and \"repatriating global supply chains\". He is also a strong opponent of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nNavarro was born on July 15, 1949, in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/candidates/election.guide/text/CA49.shtml|title=AllPolitics \u2013 Congressional Races \u2013 California District 49|website=www.cnn.com}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{cite magazine |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |title=Peter Navarro Used To Be a Democrat. Now He's the Mastermind Behind Trump's Trade War |url=http://time.com/5375727/peter-navarro/ |date=August 23, 2018 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Navarro's father, Alfred \"Al\" Navarro, a saxophonist and clarinetist, led a [[house band]], which played summers in [[New Hampshire]] and winters in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99097793/|title=Orchestra Leader is Dead from Detroit, Michigan on January 2, 1972 \u00b7 Page 32|newspaper= Detroit Free Press |accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was 9 or 10.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-05-02/trump-s-trade-warrior-is-the-most-unpopular-economist-in-the-class|title=Trump's Trade Warrior Is the Most Unpopular Economist in the Class|date=May 2, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>  Subsequently, he lived with his mother, Evelyn Littlejohn, a [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] secretary, in [[Palm Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-08/local/me-4514_1_peter-navarro|title=Navarro Says Loan for Race Was Inherited: Mayoral candidate admits $300,000 was given to him by his mother, but all the money has been spent|first=Leonard|last=Bernstein|date=August 8, 1992|newspaper=LA Times|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> He lived in [[Bethesda, Maryland]] in a one-bedroom apartment with his mother and brother during his teenage years.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nNavarro went to [[Tufts University]] on a full academic scholarship,<ref name=\":23\" /> graduating in 1972 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He then spent three years in the [[Peace Corps|U.S. Peace Corps]], serving in Thailand.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\"cv\" /> He earned a [[Master of Public Administration]] from [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in 1979, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Economics]] from Harvard under the supervision of [[Richard E. Caves]] in 1986.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web |url=https://merage.uci.edu/_files/documents/faculty-profiles/Navarro-Peter-CV.pdf|title= Peter Navarro Curriculum Vitae |last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=August 2016|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Policy analysis===\nNavarro's policy prescriptions include that \"U.S. should be tough on trade, crack down on intellectual property theft, tax Chinese exports, combat Chinese mercantilism, [and] bring jobs home.\"<ref name=ct />\n\n===Academic career===\nFrom 1981 through 1985, he was a research associate at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]'s Energy and Environmental Policy Center. From 1985 through 1988, he taught at the [[University of California, San Diego]] and the [[University of San Diego]].<ref name = UT>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-peter-navarro-tariffs-san-diego-20180306-htmlstory.html |title=Former San Diego politician Peter Navarro is fighting for Trump's tariffs|last=Hamblin|first=Abby|date=March 6, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> In 1989 he moved to the [[University of California, Irvine]] as a professor of economics and public policy. He continued on the UC Irvine faculty for more than 20 years and is now a professor emeritus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://merage.uci.edu/research-faculty/faculty-directory/Peter-Navarro.html|title=Faculty Directory|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He has worked on energy issues and the relationship between the United States and [[Asia]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|title=Peter Navarro Bio |last=Navarro |first=Peter|website=The Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103004035/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|archivedate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> He has received multiple teaching awards for [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] courses he has taught.<ref name=PMSB-Awards />\n\nAs a doctoral student in 1984, Navarro wrote a book entitled ''The Policy Game: How Special Interests and Ideologues are Stealing America'', which discussed that special interest groups had led the United States to \"a point in its history where it cannot grow and prosper.\" In the book he also called for greater worker's compensation to help those who had lost jobs to trade and foreign competition. His doctoral thesis on why corporations donate to charity is one of his most highly-cited works. He has also done research in the topic of wind energy with Frank Harris, a former student of his.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Publications===\nNavarro is a prolific author with over a dozen books written on various topics in economics and specializing in issues of balance of trade. He has published peer-reviewed economics research on energy policy, charity, deregulation and the economics of trash collection.<ref name=\"ct\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-08-01/peter-navarro-is-the-economist-whose-ideas-guide-trump|title=Here's the Economist Whose Ideas Guide Trump|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|author-link=Tyler Cowen|date=August 1, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Google Scholar Citations |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=usrEMP4AAAAJ&hl=en |website=scholar.google.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Navarro \"is a prolific writer, but has no publications in top-tier academic journals... [although] his research interests are broader than the average economist\u2019s.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/briefing/2017/01/21/peter-navarro-is-about-to-become-one-of-the-worlds-most-powerful-economists|title=Peter Navarro is about to become one of the world's most powerful economists|journal=The Economist|access-date=December 8, 2018|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' is a book published by [[Financial Times|FT Press]] in (2006). Navarro examines China as an emerging [[world power]] confronting challenges at home and abroad as it struggles to exert itself in the [[economic globalization|global market]]. He also discusses how China's role in international commerce is creating conflicts with nations around the world over energy, natural resources, the environment, [[intellectual property]], and other issues. A review in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' describes the book as \"comprehensive\" and \"contemporary\" and concludes that it \"will teach readers to understand the dragon, just not how to vanquish it\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6386391.html?q=The+Coming+China+Wars ''Publishers Weekly review of The Coming China Wars], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', October 30, 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Professor Peter Navarro of the Business School at University of California, Irvine talks his work \"Death by China\" and how China cheats in the world trade system @ University of Michigan-4.jpg|thumb|Professor Peter Navarro discusses his work, ''[[Death by China]]'', arguing China cheats in the world trade system at [[University of Michigan]] in 2012]]\n''[[Death by China]]'' (2011) is a book by Navarro and Greg Autry. According to ''The Economist'', \"the core allegations Mr. Navarro makes against China are not all that controversial. He accuses China of keeping its currency cheap . . . He deplores China\u2019s practice of forcing American firms to hand over intellectual property as a condition of access to its market. He notes, correctly, that Chinese firms pollute the environment more freely and employ workers in far worse conditions than American rules allow.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro argues that China violates fair trade by \"illegal export subsidies and currency manipulation, effectively flooding the U.S. markets\" and unfairly making it \"virtually impossible\" for American companies to compete.<ref name=rs>{{cite web|title=Review: 'Death by China' |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948072?refcatid=31|website=Variety|author=Ronnie Scheib|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> It is a critique of \"global capitalism\" including foreign labor practices and environmental protection.<ref name=\"Salon\">Andrew O'Hehir, [http://www.salon.com/2012/08/22/chinas_not_so_secret_plan_for_world_domination/ \"China\u2019s not-so-secret plan for world domination\"], ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'', August 21, 2012.</ref> Currency manipulation and subsidies are stated as reasons that \"American companies cannot compete because they're not competing with Chinese companies, they're competing with the Chinese government.\"<ref name=ng>[[Neil Genzlinger]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/24/movies/death-by-china-documentary-directed-by-peter-navarro.html \"Casting Blame for Jobs That Vanish\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 23, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Navarro directed and produced a [[documentary film]] based on his book, ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins |first1=Olivera |title=Economist Peter Navarro says U.S. manufacturing is suffering 'Death by China' |url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2012/09/film_says_us_manufacturing_is.html|website=The Cleveland Plain Dealer |accessdate=January 19, 2017|date=September 7, 2012}}</ref> The film, described as \"fervently anti-China\",<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Katie|last=Quan|year=2017|title=Prospects for US-China Union Relations in the Era of Xi and Trump|journal=International Union Rights|page=13|volume=24|issue=4|doi=10.14213/inteuniorigh.24.4.0011 }}</ref> was released under the same title and narrated by [[Martin Sheen]]. From 2011 until 2016, Navarro was a frequent guest on the radio program the John Batchelor Show.\n\n===Political career===\n\n====Politics and campaigns for public office====\nWhile teaching at UC Irvine, Navarro ran unsuccessfully for office in [[San Diego, California]] five times.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name = UT/> In 1992, he [[San Diego mayoral election, 1992|ran for mayor]], finishing first (38.2%) in the primary, but lost with 48% to [[Susan Golding]] in the runoff.<ref name=CSD-M /> During his mayoral campaign, Navarro ran on a no-growth platform.<ref name=\"SanDiegoSprawl\">{{Cite book|title=The Failure of Planning: Permitting Sprawl in San Diego Suburbs, 1970\u20131999|last=Hogan|first=Richard|publisher=[[Ohio State University Press]]|year=2002|isbn=978-0814251041|location=United States|page=[https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119 119]|url=https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119}}</ref> In 1993, he ran for San Diego city council and in 1994 for San Diego County board of supervisors.<ref name = UT/> In 1996, he ran for the [[California's 49th congressional district|49th Congressional District]] as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee, but lost to Republican [[Brian Bilbray]], 52.7% to 41.9%.<ref name=BP-CA49 /> In 2001, Navarro ran in a special election to fill the District 6 San Diego city council seat, but lost in a special election with 7.85% of the vote.<ref name=CSD-CD6 />\n\nNavarro supported President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[phase-out of incandescent light bulbs]], the adoption of [[Wind power|wind energy]], and [[carbon tax]]es in order to stop [[global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/a-pit-bull-for-climate-could-soon-sit-next-to-trump/|title=A \"Pit Bull\" for Climate Could Soon Sit Next to Trump|last=News|first=Robin Bravender,Zack Colman,E&E|work=Scientific American|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Trump campaign advisor ====\nIn 2016, Navarro served as an economic policy adviser to Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"appoint\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/greatagain/navarro-national-trade-council-c2d90c10eacb|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Appoints Dr. Peter Navarro to Head the White House National Trade Council|first=The Transition|last=Team|date=December 21, 2016|website=Medium}}</ref> He advocated for an [[Isolationism|isolationist]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] American foreign policy.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|title=White House At A Crossroads After Cohn|last=Soergel|first=Andrew|date=March 7, 2018|website=US News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308014013/https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Navarro and the international private equity investor [[Wilbur Ross]] authored an economic plan for Trump campaign in September 2016.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan|title=New White Paper on Donald J. Trump's Economic Plan |website=www.donaldjtrump.com|access-date=March 6, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045918/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan |archivedate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Navarro was invited to be an adviser after [[Jared Kushner]], while he was researching China for Trump, saw on Amazon that Navarro co-wrote ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref name=\"Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon\">{{cite web|last1=Vladimirov|first1=Nikita|title=Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/328969-report-kushner-found-trump-economic-advisor-navarro-by-browsing|website=TheHill|accessdate=April 18, 2017|language=English|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> When told that the [[Tax Policy Center]] assessment of Trump's economic plan would reduce federal revenues by $6 trillion and reduce economic growth in the long term, Navarro said that the analysis demonstrated \"a high degree of analytical and political malfeasance\".<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/10/24/trumps-advisers-see-another-conspiracy-far-from-the-campaign-trail/|title=Trump's advisers see another conspiracy \u2013 far from the campaign trail|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> When the Peterson Institute for International Affairs estimated that Trump's economic plan would cost millions of Americans their jobs, Navarro said that writers at the Peterson Institute \"weave a false narrative and they come up with some phony numbers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2016/09/19/trump-adviser-bullish-wake-tax-trade-critiques/ |title=Trump Adviser Bullish in Wake of Tax, Trade Critiques|last=Rainey|first=Ryan|date=September 19, 2016|website=Morning Consult |access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> According to MIT economist [[Simon Johnson (economist)|Simon Johnson]], the economic plan essay authored by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Donald Trump during the campaign had projections \"based on assumptions so unrealistic that they seem to have come from a different planet. If the United States really did adopt Trump's plan, the result would be an immediate and unmitigated disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/trump-insane-economic-plan-by-simon-johnson-2016-09?barrier=accessreg|title=Trump's Magical Economic Thinking|last=Johnson|first=Simon|date=September 30, 2016 |work=Project Syndicate|access-date=March 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When 370 economists, including nineteen Nobel laureates, signed a letter warning against Donald Trump's stated economic policies in November 2016, Navarro said that the letter was \"an embarrassment to the corporate offshoring wing of the economist profession who continues to insist bad trade deals are good for America.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-of-prominent-us-economists-warn-against-voting-trump/|title=Hundreds of US economists warn against voting Trump|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, with [[Wilbur Ross]] and [[Andy Puzder]], Navarro co-authored the essay titled \"Economic Analysis of Donald Trump's Contract with the American Voter\".<ref>[[Wilbur Ross]], [[Andy Puzder]] & Peter Navarro, [http://www.publicnow.com/view/26F924AB8FA783A28FEA3EE8943635B4F0574556?2016-10-31-14:32:09+00:00-xxx4035]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald J. Trump for President, Inc.]], October 30, 2016</ref>\n\n====White House trade advisor====\n[[File:Peter Navarro, Director of the White House National Trade Council, Addresses in the Oval Office before U.S. President Donald Trump Signs Executive Orders Regarding Trade on March 31, 2017 4.jpg|thumb|Director Peter Navarro addresses President [[Donald Trump]]'s promises to American people, workers, and domestic manufacturers ('''[https://assets.donaldjtrump.com/DJT_DeclaringAmericanEconomicIndependence.pdf Declaring American Economic Independence]''' on June 28, 2016) in the [[Oval Office]] with [[U.S. Vice President|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] and [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Wilbur Ross]] before President Trump signs [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Orders]] regarding trade in March 2017<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-regarding-omnibus-report-significant-trade Presidential Executive Order Regarding the Omnibus Report on Significant Trade Deficits], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-establishing-enhanced-collection-and Presidential Executive Order on Establishing Enhanced Collection and Enforcement of Antidumping and Countervailing Duties and Violations of Trade and Customs Laws], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref>]]\nOn December 21, 2016, Navarro was selected by President-elect Trump to head a newly created position, as director of the [[White House National Trade Council]].<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title='Death by China' author to lead Trump trade office|url=https://www.ft.com/content/71a201d2-c7b3-11e6-8f29-9445cac8966f|website=www.ft.com|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> He outlines President Trump's trade policy as aiming to create jobs, revive the manufacturing sector, and improve the country's trade balance. He warned that trade deficits could jeopardize U.S. national security by allowing unfriendly nations to encroach on American supply chains. One of his main missions is to focus on behaviors by other countries that he considers abusive, cheating, illegal, and unfair against the U.S.<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4659659/peter-navarro-outlines-trump-administration-trade-policy-priorities Peter Navarro Outlines Trump Administration Trade Policy Priorities], [[C-SPAN]], June 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/videos/2017-03-31/navarro-says-not-all-trade-deficits-necessarily-bad-video Peter Navarro Says Trade Deficits Aren't Always Bad], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], March 31, 2017</ref>\n\n====Director of Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy====\nIn April 2017, the National Trade Council became part of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], of which Navarro was appointed Director.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news| last1=Cook | first1=Nancy | last2=Restuccia | first2=Andrew |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/peter-navarro-trump-trade-240611|title=Trump's trade warrior prowls the West Wing|date=July 17, 2017|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> By September 2017, the Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy had been folded into the National Economic Council, which meant that Navarro would report to NEC Director [[Gary Cohn (investment banker)|Gary Cohn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/27/peter-navarro-trade-office-national-economic-council-243217|title=Kelly folds Navarro's trade shop into National Economic Council|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, several media outlets reported that Navarro's influence in the administration was rising again and that he would likely be promoted from the secondary billet of Deputy Assistant to the President to Assistant to the President, giving Navarro parity with the NEC Director.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Swanson | first1=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, a Top Trade Skeptic, Is Ascendant | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/25/us/politics/peter-navarro-trade.html | date=February 25, 2018 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Lynch | first1=David J. | last2=Damian | first2=Paletta | title=Trump Tilts Toward Hard-Liners Ahead of Key Trade Decisions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/trump-tilts-toward-hard-liners-ahead-of-key-trade-decisions/2018/02/26/ffe93e46-1b32-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html | date=February 26, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Josh Rogin]], writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', reported that Navarro had used his prior time of lower influence to lead several low-profile policy items, such as working to increase military funding, drafting [[:s:Executive Order 13806|Executive Order 13806]], and leading the effort to solve a dispute between the United States and [[Qatar]] over the Open Skies Agreement between the two countries.<ref name=\"joshwapo\">{{cite news | last1=Rogin | first1=Josh | title=How Peter Navarro Got His Groove Back | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2018/02/27/how-peter-navarro-got-his-groove-back/ | date=February 27, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn explaining his role in the Trump administration, Navarro said that he is there to \"provide the underlying analytics that confirm [Trump's] intuition [on trade]. And his intuition is always right in these matters.\"<ref name=\"Coy\" />\n\nIn June 2018, Navarro said that there was \"a special place in hell\" for Justin Trudeau, the Prime Minister of Canada, after Trudeau said that Canada would respond with retaliatory tariffs since the United States had placed tariffs on Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/10/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Peter Navarro says 'there's a special place in hell' for Justin Trudeau|last= Watkins|first=Eli|work=CNN|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> The Prime Minister's point-of-view and Canada's response to these tariffs were already public and well-known when Navarro made this comment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/white-house-adviser-kudlow-trump-trudeau-g7-summit-blame-1.4700061|title='Special place in hell': Trump advisers blast Trudeau for comments at G7 summit {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>  Navarro later apologized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/12/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Navarro sorry after saying there's a 'special place in hell' for Trudeau|first=Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Navarro said that Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States as \"a brilliant move\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/31/mnuchin-and-lighthizer-were-opposed-to-trump-tariffs-on-mexico-source-says.html|title=Mnuchin and Lighthizer opposed Trump tariffs on Mexico, source says|last=Higgins|first=Kayla Tausche,Tucker|date=2019-05-31|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, after being tasked by the President to combat China's usage of international mail rates to more cheaply ship products into the US, Navarro successfully led a diplomatic effort to the third Extraordinary Congress of the [[Universal Postal Union]] where it agreed member countries could be able to opt-in to self-declare their rates starting in July 2020, after repeated threats from the Trump administration to leave the UPU unless global postage rates were changed so countries like China could no longer unfairly benefit from international delivery prices, particularly when it came to e-commerce deliveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/26/trump-scores-a-big-victory-on-stamps-postal-union-terminal-dues-china/|title=Trump Scores a Big Victory-on Stamps|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-un-postal/u-n-postal-union-clinches-deal-to-keep-u-s-in-club-idUSKBN1WA247|title=U.N. postal union clinches deal to keep U.S. in club|last= Nebehay|first=Stephanie|work=Reuters|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavarro continued to promote policies challenging amid trade negotiations between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Schlesinger | first1=Jacob M. | last2=Salama | first2=Vivian | title=New White House Report, Authored by Trade Hawk, Blasts Chinese 'Economic Aggression'  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-white-house-report-authored-by-trade-hawk-blasts-chinese-economic-aggression-1529456401 | date=June 19, 2018 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=In the Battles Over Trump's Trade Wars, Hawkish Adviser Navarro Endures  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-the-battles-over-trumps-trade-wars-hawkish-adviser-navarro-endures-11576943074 | date=December 21, 2019 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Rappeport | first1=Alan | last2=Swanson | first2=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, Trump's Trade Warrior, Has Not Made His Peace With China | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/26/us/politics/peter-navarro-china-trade.html | date=December 26, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro worked with the DHS to initiate a crackdown on counterfeited and pirated e-commerce goods from overseas,<ref>{{cite web | last1=Shepardson | first1=David | title=U.S. to unveil crackdown on counterfeit, pirated e-commerce goods | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-counterfeiting/u-s-to-unveil-crackdown-on-counterfeit-pirated-e-commerce-goods-idUSKBN1ZN02E | date=January 23, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/us/politics/us-cracks-down-on-counterfeits-in-a-warning-shot-to-china.html |title=U.S. Cracks Down on Counterfeits in a Warning Shot to China - The New York Times |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= January 24, 2020|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mauldin | first1=William | last2=Leary | first2=Alex | title=U.S. Signals Crackdown on Counterfeit Goods Sold Online  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-signals-crackdown-on-counterfeit-goods-sold-online-11579820400 | date=January 24, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/24/dhs-report-targets-online-counterfeit-sales-on-amazon-e-commerce.html |title=DHS report targets online counterfeit sales on Amazon, e-commerce |publisher=Cnbc.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and he promoted the administration's actions on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jessica Bursztynsky |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/16/navarro-to-amazon-ebay-china-trade-deal-cracks-down-on-counterfeits.html |title=Navarro to Amazon, eBay: China trade deal cracks down on counterfeits |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=2020-01-16 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Peter |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/perspectives/peter-navarro-e-commerce-counterfeit-products/index.html |title=Navarro: Counterfeits harm Americans and threaten national security. Trump has a plan to combat them (opinion) |publisher=CNN |date=2020-01-31 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> Trump signed an executive order on the matter on January 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web | title=Trump signs executive order aimed at preventing sales of counterfeit goods from overseas | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-shipments/trump-signs-executive-order-aimed-at-preventing-sales-of-counterfeit-goods-from-overseas-idUSKBN1ZU35P | date=January 31, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, it was reported that Navarro was conducting his own investigation into the identity of the author of [[I Am Part of the Resistance Inside the Trump Administration|an anonymous op-ed in ''The New York Times'']] criticizing the Trump Administration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Suebsaeng | first1=Asawin | last2=Markay | first2=Lachlan | title=Trump's Top Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Has a Side Project: Secretly Hunting for 'Anonymous' | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-top-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-has-a-side-project-secretly-hunting-for-anonymous | date=February 17, 2020 | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Infrastructure plan====\nDuring the campaign Navarro, together with [[Wilbur Ross]] who became Trump's [[Commerce Secretary]], designed a $1 trillion infrastructure development plan for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name=\"peternavarro.com\">{{cite web|url=http://peternavarro.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/infrastructurereport.pdf|title=Infrastructure report|date=|publisher=peternavarro.com|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> The plan called for $137 billion in tax credits to private business to induce them to financing the bulk of infrastructure spending. Economists across the political spectrum derided the proposal.<ref name=\"Mufson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/economists-pan-infrastructure-plan-championed-by-trump-nominees/2017/01/17/0ed1ad5e-dc5e-11e6-918c-99ede3c8cafa_story.html|title=Economists pan infrastructure plan championed by Trump nominees|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=January 17, 2017|via=www.washingtonpost.com|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> Trump released a $1.5 trillion version of this plan in February 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/infrastructure/373408-white-house-releases-55-page-infrastructure-proposal|title=White House releases 55-page, $1.5 trillion infrastructure plan|first=Mallory|last=Shelbourne|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> but the Republican-controlled Congress showed little enthusiasm for the proposal, with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] reporting, \"President Trump's infrastructure plan appears to have crashed and burned in Congress\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/377681-trumps-infrastructure-push-hits-wall-in-congress|title=Trump's infrastructure push hits wall in Congress|first=Dustin|last=Weaver|date=March 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Coronavirus pandemic====\nOn January 29, 2020, Navarro issued a memo warning that [[Coronavirus disease 2019|novel coronavirus]] could \"evolv[e] into a full-blown pandemic, imperiling the lives of millions of Americans\" and that the \"risk of a worst-case pandemic scenario should not be overlooked\". He argued for restrictions on travel from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trade Adviser Warned White House in January of Risks of a Pandemic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/us/politics/navarro-warning-trump-coronavirus.html |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Klar | first1=Rebecca | title=Trump adviser warned of coronavirus threat in January | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/491490-trump-adviser-warned-of-coronavirus-threat-in-january | date=April 7, 2020 | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Navarro wrote another memo on February 23, 2020, arguing that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] \"could infect as many as 100 million Americans, with a loss of life of as many as 1-2 million souls\" and calling for an \"immediate supplemental appropriation of at least $3 billion.\"<ref>{{cite web | last1=Swan | first1=Jonathan | last2=Talev | first2=Margaret | title=Navarro memos warning of mass coronavirus death circulated in January | url=https://www.axios.com/exclusive-navarro-deaths-coronavirus-memos-january-da3f08fb-dce1-4f69-89b5-ea048f8382a9.html | date=April 7, 2020 | work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] | accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> At the same time that Navarro was issuing warnings, he said in public that the American people had \"nothing to worry about\" regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/politics/peter-navarro-coronavirus/index.html|title=Navarro publicly said Americans had 'nothing to worry about' while privately warning coronavirus could cost lives and dollars|author1=Em Steck |author2=Andrew Kaczynski|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, Trump appointed Navarro to coordinate the federal government's [[Defense Production Act]] policy response during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489938-trump-names-new-defense-production-act-coordinator-for-coronavirus|title=Trump names new Defense Production Act coordinator for coronavirus fight|first=Morgan|last=Chalfant|date=March 27, 2020|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Pappas | first1=Alex | title=Trump appoints Navarro to lead Defense Production Act efforts after forcing GM to make ventilators | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-aide-navarro-lead-defense-production-act-efforts | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=\u2018This is War\u2019: President\u2019s Equipment Czar to Use Full Powers to Fight Coronavirus | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-is-war-presidents-equipment-czar-to-use-full-powers-to-fight-coronavirus-11585435836 | date=March 28, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro clashed with [[Anthony Fauci]], the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]], over whether the administration should promote the use of [[hydroxychloroquine]] to treat the virus despite being unproven.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-hydroxychloroquine-white-house-01306286-0bbc-4042-9bfe-890413c6220d.html|title=Inside the epic White House blowup over \"game-changer\" hydroxychloroquine|last=Swan|first=Jonathan|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views on trade ==\n{{main|International trade|Commercial policy|Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign}}\nNavarro has been a staunch critic of trade with China and strong proponent of reducing U.S. trade deficits. He has attacked Germany, Japan and China for currency manipulation. He has called for increasing the size of the American manufacturing sector, setting high tariffs, and repatriating global supply chains. He was a fierce opponent of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\nAccording to [[Bloomberg News]], Navarro had \"roots as a mainstream economist\" as he voiced support for free trade in his 1984 book ''The Policy Game''. He changed his positions as he saw \"the globalist erosion of the American economy\" develop.<ref name=\"Coy\"/>\n\nAccording to ''Politico'', Navarro's economic theories are \"considered fringe\" by his fellow economists.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2017/03/trump-trade-attack-dog-peter-navarro-000353|title=Trump's attack dog on trade|last=|first=|date=|work=The Agenda|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> A ''New Yorker'' reporter described Navarro's views on trade and China as so radical \"that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/trumps-muse-on-u-s-trade-with-china|title=Trump's Muse on U.S. Trade with China|last=|first=|date=October 12, 2016|website=The New Yorker|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's views on trade and China are so radical, however, that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.}}</ref> The ''Economist'' described Navarro as having \"oddball views\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21721937-donald-trumps-economic-strategy-unimaginative-and-incoherent-cooking-up-economic-policy|title=Cooking up an economic policy|website=The Economist|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> The George Mason University economist [[Tyler Cowen]] has described him as \"one of the most versatile and productive American economists of the last few decades\", but Cowen noted that he disagreed with his views on trade, which he claimed go \"against a strong professional consensus.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> University of Michigan economist [[Justin Wolfers]] described Navarro's views as \"far outside the mainstream,\" noting that \"he endorses few of the key tenets of\" the economics profession.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/upshot/why-most-economists-are-so-worried-about-trump.html|title=Why Most Economists Are So Worried About Trump|last=Wolfers|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|access-date=January 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331|quote=the only official who identifies as an economist\u2014Peter Navarro, who earned a Harvard Ph.D. in economics and will head up the newly formed National Trade Council\u2014stands so far outside the mainstream that he endorses few of the key tenets of the profession.|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> According to Lee Branstetter, economics professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University|Carnegie Mellon]] and trade expert with the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], Navarro \"was never a part of the group of economists who ever studied the global free-trade system ... He doesn't publish in journals. What he's writing and saying right now has nothing to do with what he got his Harvard Ph.D. in ... he doesn't do research that would meet the scientific standards of that community.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://businessinsider.com/what-is-trumpenomics-according-to-peter-navarro-2017-1|title=The clearest articulation of what Trump wants to do to America's economy comes from one person|last=|first=|date=|work=Business Insider|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Marcus Noland, an economist at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, described a tax and trade paper written by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Trump as \"a complete misunderstanding of international trade, on their part.\"<ref name=\":82\"/>\n\nIn August 2019, Navarro asserted the tariffs of the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]] were not hurting Americans. Citing extensive evidence to the contrary, Politifact rated Navarro's assertion \"Pants on Fire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/aug/20/peter-navarro/donald-trumps-tariffs-china-dont-hurt-americans-to/|title=Tariffs on China don't hurt Americans? Pants on Fire|website=@politifact}}</ref>\n\n=== Border adjustment tax ===\nNavarro supports a tax policy called \"border adjustment\", which, as commonly used in the [[value added taxes|VATs]] of most countries, taxes all imports at the domestic rate while rebating tax on exports, essentially transforming taxes from taxes on production to taxes on consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to criticism that the border adjustment tax could hurt U.S. companies and put jobs at risk, Navarro called it \"fake news.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Criticism of China ===\nAccording to ''Politico'', \"Navarro is perhaps the most extreme advocate in Washington, and maybe in all of economics, for an aggressive stance toward China.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Navarro put his attention to China in the mid-2000s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/13/peter-navarro-profile-national-trade-council-donald-trump-china-expert/ |title=Trump's Top China Expert Isn't a China Expert|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> His first publication on the subject is the 2006 book ''[[The Coming China Wars: Where They Will Be Fought, How They Can Be Won]]''.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/peter-navarro-trump-trade-china-214772 |title=The Most Dangerous Man in Trump World?|work=Politico|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Navarro has said that he started to examine China when he noticed that his former students were losing jobs, concluding that China was at fault.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn ''Politico''{{'}}s description of the book, \"Navarro uses military language to refer to China's trade policies, referring to its 'conquest' of the world's export markets, which has 'vaporized literally millions of manufacturing jobs and driven down wages.' ... China's aspirations are so insatiable, he claims, that eventually there will be a clash over \"our most basic of all needs\u2014bread, water, and air.'\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Navarro has described the entry of China to the World Trade Organization as one of the United States' biggest mistakes.<ref name=\":8\" /> To respond to the Chinese threat, Navarro has advocated for 43% tariffs, the repudiation of trade pacts, major increases in military expenditures and strengthened military ties with Taiwan.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"a wide range of economists have warned that curtailing trade with China would damage the American economy, forcing consumers to pay higher prices for goods and services.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/21/us/politics/peter-navarro-carl-icahn-trump-china-trade.html|title=Trump Taps Peter Navarro, Vocal Critic of China, for New Trade Post|last=Appelbaum|first=Binyamin|date=December 21, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Navarro has reportedly also encouraged President Trump to enact a 25-percent tariff on Chinese steel imports, something that \"trade experts worry... would upend global trade practices and cause countries to retaliate, potentially leading to a trade war\".<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\nNavarro has said that a large part of China's competitive advantage over the United States stems from unfair trade practices.<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro has criticized China for pollution, poor labor standards, government subsidies, producing \"contaminated, defective and cancerous\" exports, currency manipulation, and theft of US intellectual property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-06/u-s-aims-to-reclaim-global-supply-chain-trump-trade-aide-says|title=U.S. Will Reclaim Global Supply Chain, Trump Trade Aide Says|date=March 6, 2017|publisher=Bloomberg|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In his 2012 documentary, Navarro said that China caused the loss of 57,000 US factories and 25 million jobs. Navarro maintains that China manipulates its currency, and although most economists believe that it is not the case, the U.S. Treasury officially designated China as a \"Currency Manipulator\" on August 5th, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm751|title=Treasury Designates China as a Currency Manipulator {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOf the more than dozen China specialists contacted by ''Foreign Policy'', most either did not know of him or only interacted with him briefly.<ref name=\":8\" /> Kenneth Pomeranz, University of Chicago professor of Chinese History, said that his \"recollection is that [Navarro] generally avoided people who actually knew something about the country.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> Columnist [[Gordon G. Chang]] was the only China watcher contacted by ''Foreign Policy'' who defended Navarro, but even then noted that he disagreed with Navarro's claims of currency manipulation, opposition to the TPP and calls for high tariffs.<ref name=\":8\" /> James McGregor, a former chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in China, said that Navarro's books and documentary on China \"have close to zero credibility with people who know the country,\" and are filled with \"hyperbole, inaccuracies\" and a \"cartoonish caricature of China that he puts out.\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nSome of Navarro's views on China fit within the mainstream, such as criticism of Chinese currency manipulation (pre-2015), concern that China\u2019s rapid ascension to the World Trade Organization harmed the Rust Belt, and criticism of China's weak environmental regulations and poor labor standards.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Ron Vara ===\nIn six of his books about China, Navarro quotes a \"Ron Vara\", whom he describes as a China hawk and former Harvard PhD doctoral student in economics, and who says crass Sinophobic things about China and the Chinese. An investigation by the ''Chronicle'' found that this [[Author surrogate|character]] was made up, and that Ron Vara (an anagram of Navarro) appeared to represent views that Navarro himself held.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/20191015-navarro|title=Trump's 'China Muse' Has an Imaginary Friend|date=2019-10-15|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horsley |first1=Scott |title=White House Adviser Peter Navarro Calls Fictional Alter Ego An 'Inside Joke' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/18/771396016/white-house-adviser-peter-navarro-calls-fictional-alter-ego-an-inside-joke |website=npr |publisher=National Public Radio |accessdate=19 October 2019 |quote=\"As she put it, the joke wears very thin when you get to certain statements about China and the Chinese people that are quite negative,\" Bartlett said. \"Ron Vara says things that are pretty over the top, and it's hard to construe them necessarily as whimsical in the way we normally use that word.\"}}</ref> Navarro has admitted to making up the character and quoting him in his books. Economist [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]], who co-authored ''Seeds of Destruction'' with Navarro,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crook |first1=Clive |title=Hubbard and Navarro on the 'Seeds of Destruction' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2010/11/hubbard-and-navarro-on-the-seeds-of-destruction/66167/ |website=The Atlantic |publisher=The Atlantic |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> has said he was not aware that Vara was fictional and that he was not okay with it. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Arciga |first1=Julia |title=Trump Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Admits to Quoting Character He Invented in His Books |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-admits-to-quoting-character-he-invented-in-his-books |website=Daily Beast |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, a memo apparently authored by Ron Vara began circulating in Washington DC. The memo highlighted the \"Keep Tariff Argument\" and the use of tariffs against China a few days before an additional 15% tariff on $160 billion of Chinese made goods was set to be implemented. Navarro later confirmed that he had written the memo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/11/peter-navarros-alter-ego-ron-vara-shares-pro-tariff-memo-amid-trade-talks.html|title=Peter Navarro's alter ego 'Ron Vara' shares pro-tariff memo amid US-China trade talks|author=|date=December 11, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\nNavarro drew controversy when he accused Germany of using a \"grossly undervalued\" euro to \"exploit\" the US and the rest of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/57f104d2-e742-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> ''Politico'' noted that the German government does not set the value of the euro.<ref name=\":7\" /> Economists and commentators are divided on the accuracy of Navarro's remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2017/02/is-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=Is Germany a currency manipulator? |publisher=Bruegel|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/485bace6-ea0a-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said that Navarro was right and wrong at the same time: \"Yes, Germany in effect has an undervalued currency relative to what it would have without the euro... But does this mean that the euro as a whole is undervalued against the dollar? Probably not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/02/01/germany-the-euro-and-currency-manipulation/|title=Germany, the Euro, and Currency Manipulation|website=Paul Krugman Blog|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Boston University economist [[Laurence Kotlikoff]] described Navarro's accusation of Germany as a currency manipulator as \"#stupideconomics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kotlikoff/2017/02/01/the-latest-stupideconomics-peter-navarro-calls-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=The Latest #StupidEconomics \u2013 Peter Navarro Calls Germany A 'Currency Manipulator'|last=Kotlikoff|first=Laurence|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nNavarro argues that the decline in US manufacturing jobs is chiefly due to \"unfair trade practices and bad trade deals. And if you don't believe that, just go to the booming factories in Germany, in Japan, in Korea, in China, in Malaysia, in Vietnam, in Indonesia, in Italy\u2014every place that we're running deficits with.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/03/526621048/peter-navarro-a-bricklayer-of-trumps-protectionist-wall|title=Peter Navarro: A 'Bricklayer' Of Trump's Protectionist Wall |publisher=NPR|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> However, many economists attribute the decline in manufacturing jobs chiefly to [[automation]] and other innovations that allow manufacturing firms to produce more goods with fewer workers, rather than trade.<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/27/news/economy/donald-trump-economy/index.html|title=Trump will grow the economy like Reagan, says adviser Peter Navarro|last=Long|first=Heather|date=June 27, 2016|website=CNN Money|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNavarro has been a proponent of strengthening the manufacturing sector's role in the national economy: \"We envision a more Germany-style economy, where 20 percent of our workforce is in manufacturing. ... And we're not talking about banging tin in the back room.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"experts on manufacturing ... doubt that the government can significantly increase factory employment, noting that mechanization is the major reason fewer people are working in factories.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Opposition to NAFTA ===\nNavarro has called for the United States to leave the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and has tried to convince President Trump to initiate a withdrawal.<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\n=== Repatriation of global supply chains ===\nNavarro has called for repatriating global supply chains.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> According to ''Politico'''s [[Jacob Heilbrunn]], such a move \"would be enormously costly and take years to execute\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Trade as a national security risk ===\nNavarro has framed trade as a national security risk.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-makes-cutting-trade-deficit-top-priority-1488815842|title=Trump Adviser Peter Navarro: Trade Deficits Endanger U.S. National Security|last=Timiraos|first=Nick|date=March 6, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nNavarro has characterized foreign purchases of U.S. companies as a threat to national security, but according to NPR, this is \"a fringe view that puts him at odds with the vast majority of economists.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/03/10/519488848/trump-advisers-warning-about-food-supply-takeover-met-with-skepticism|title=Trump Adviser's Warning About Food Supply Takeover Met With Skepticism|last=|first=|date=|work=NPR.org|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en|quote=Peter Navarro says foreign companies buying up U.S. corporations are posing a threat to national security.}}</ref> Dartmouth economist Douglas Irwin noted that the US government already reviews foreign purchases of companies with military or strategic value, and has on occasion rejected such deals.<ref name=\":2\" /> Irwin said that Navarro had not substantiated his claim with any evidence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro has also said that the United States has \"already begun to lose control of [its] food supply chain\", which according to NPR, \"sounded pretty off-the-wall to a number of economists\" who noted that the US is a massive exporter of food.<ref name=\":2\" /> Dermot Hayes, an agribusiness economist at Iowa State University, described Navarro's statement as \"uninformed\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro criticized the [[outsourcing]] of critical materials \u2014 like the production of essential [[Medical device|medical supplies]] \u2014 to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade deficits ===\n{{main|Balance of trade}}\nNavarro is a proponent of the notion that [[trade deficit]]s are bad in and of themselves, a view which is widely rejected by trade experts and economists.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/06/economists-take-aim-at-trump-trade-theory-again-peter-navarro-bilateral-multilateral-trade-deals-china-germany-national-security/ |title=Economists Take Aim at Trump Trade Theory \u2013 Again |first=Robbie |last=Gramer |website=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's comments drew skepticism from trade experts and economists across the political spectrum\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro and Ross say that getting rid of the trade deficit and boosting investment would also spur faster economic growth, which would bring in $1.74 trillion in tax revenue over a decade.\"}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/03/07/trump-rails-against-the-trade-deficit-but-economists-say-theres-no-easy-way-for-him-to-make-it-go-away/|title=Analysis {{!}} Trump rails against trade deficit, but economists say there's no easy way for him to make it go away|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In a white paper co-authored with Wilbur Ross, Navarro stated, \"when a country runs a trade deficit by importing more than it exports, this subtracts from growth.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/navarros-trade-views-misguided-dangerous|title=Navarro's Trade Views 'Misguided', 'Dangerous'|date=December 23, 2016|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref> In a ''Wall Street Journal'' op-ed defending his views, Navarro stated, \"If we are able to reduce our trade deficits through tough, smart negotiations, we should be able to increase our growth.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-white-house-worries-about-trade-deficits-1488751930|title=Why the White House Worries About Trade Deficits|last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=March 5, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Harvard University economics professor [[Greg Mankiw|Gregory Mankiw]] has said that Navarro's views on the trade deficit are based on the kind of mistakes that \"even a freshman at the end of ec 10 knows.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2016/09/trumponomics.html|title=Greg Mankiw's Blog: Trumponomics|last=|first=|date=|website=gregmankiw.blogspot.com|language=en|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> Tufts University professor [[Daniel W. Drezner]] said about Navarro's op-ed, \"as someone who's written on this topic I could not for the life of me understand his reasoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2017/03/09/why-the-trump-administration-hates-multilateral-trade-agreements-the-most/|title=Perspective {{!}} Why the Trump administration hates multilateral trade agreements the most|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> According to [[Tyler Cowen]], \"close to no one\" in the economics profession agrees with Navarro's idea that a trade deficit is bad in and of itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208134200/http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archivedate=2016-12-08|title=What You Should Know About the Professor Who Has Trump's Ear on the Economy |publisher= The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 8, 2016|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> Nobel laureate [[Angus Deaton]] described Navarro's attitude on trade deficits as \"an old-fashioned mercantilist position.\"<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' magazine has described Navarro's views on the trade deficit as \"dodgy economics\",<ref name=\":0\" /> while the ''Financial Times'' has described them as \"poor economics\".<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eea50292-0331-11e7-aa5b-6bb07f5c8e12|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Economists Noah Smith,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-12-28/trump-s-trade-chief-peter-navarro-makes-a-rookie-mistake|title=Trump's Trade Chief Makes a Rookie Mistake|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=December 28, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Sumner]], [[Olivier Blanchard]],<ref name=\":10\" /> and Phil Levy<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/phillevy/2017/03/06/white-house-whiffs-on-trade-deficit-defense/#7aea21f06b6c|title=White House Whiffs On Trade Deficit Defense|last=Levy |first=Phil|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> have also criticized Navarro's views on the trade deficit. Dan Ikenson, director of the [[Cato Institute]]'s Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies goes so far as to call Navarro a \"charlatan\" and says that \"99.9 per cent of respectable economists would eschew\" what he says: \"He says imports deduct from output, and he calls that accounting identity the 'economic growth formula'. He thinks that for every dollar we import, our GDP is reduced by a dollar. I don't know how he got his PhD at Harvard.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=The purge of April: Trump's new advisers pour on the gas |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/the-purge-of-april-trump-s-new-advisers-pour-on-the-gas-1.4705201 |website=www.cbc.ca |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to Trans-Pacific Partnership ===\nNavarro opposes the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/238473-parsing-the-trans-pacific-partnership-agreement|title=Parsing the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=April 13, 2015|work=The Hill|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In an April 2015 op-ed, Navarro said, \"To woo us, their spinmeisters boast the TPP will spur American exports to stimulate sorely needed economic growth. In truth, the American economy will suffer severely. This is because the TPP will hammer two main drivers of economic growth\u2014domestic investment and 'net exports.'\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Navarro said in March 2017 that TPP \"would have been a \"death knell\" to America's auto and vehicle parts industry that we \"urgently need to bring back to full life.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> ''Politico''<nowiki/>'s Jacob Heilbrunn and ''the'' ''Economist'' argue that there may be a disconnect between Navarro's policy on China and his opposition to the TPP, as scuttling the TPP will strengthen China's hand.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Library resources box|about=no|by=yes}}\n\n* ''Crouching Tiger: What China's Militarism Means for the World'' (2015)\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBe2wpZqN0s Episode 1: Will There Be War With China?]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUA_wh88fYc Episode 2: The World At the Tip of a Chinese Spear]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odiv79hZhB4 Episode 3: The Wild Card of North Korea]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HEjlcmfNt3Y Episode 4: The Unsinkable Aircraft Carrier of Taiwan]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1csrTOxJ8JM Episode 5: Will There Be War Between China and Japan?]\n* ''[[Death by China (book)|Death by China: Confronting the Dragon \u2013 A Global Call to Action]]'' (2011)\n* ''Seeds of Destruction'' (with [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]]) (2010)\n* ''Always a Winner: Finding Your Competitive Advantage in an Up and Down Economy'' (2009)\n* ''The Well-Timed Strategy: Managing the Business Cycle for Competitive Advantage'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' (2006)\n* ''What the Best MBAs Know'' (2005)\n* ''Principles of Economics: Business, Banking, Finance, and Your Everyday Life'' (2005)\n* ''When the Market Moves, Will You Be Ready?'' (2003)\n* ''If It's Raining in Brazil, Buy Starbucks''<ref name=ISBN /> (2001)\n* ''Bill Clinton's Agenda for America'' (1993)\n* ''Job Opportunities Under Clinton/Gore'' (with Craig Adams) (1993)\n* ''The Policy Game'' (1984)\n* ''The Dimming of America: The Real Costs of Electric Utility Regulation'' (1984)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"PMSB-Awards\">{{cite web|title=Teaching Awards|url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|publisher=The Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826230801/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|archivedate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BP-CA49\">{{cite web|title=California's 49th Congressional District Elections|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California%27s_49th_Congressional_District|publisher=Ballotpedia|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-M\">{{cite web|title=Election Results \u2013 Mayor, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/mayorresults.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-CD6\">{{cite web|title=Election History \u2013 Council District 6, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/cd6results.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ISBN\">{{cite web|title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Books|url=http://www.isbnsearch.org/search?s=peter+navarro|publisher=ISBN Search|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Peter Navarro}}\n* [http://www.peternavarro.com/ Official site]\n* {{C-SPAN|Peter Navarro 02}}\n* [http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589 UCI Faculty Profile]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2304583/ Death by China] at [[IMDb]]\n\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Navarro, Peter}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American economics writers]]\n[[Category:Economists from California]]\n[[Category:Economists from Florida]]\n[[Category:Economists from Maryland]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Peace Corps volunteers]]\n[[Category:People from Bethesda, Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Irvine faculty]]\n[[Category:Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Navarro"}
{"title_page": "Lekach", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Lekach(Lekakh)\n| image            = Honey Cake.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Jewish honey cake, honey cake\n| country          = {{flag|Israel}}\n| region           = [[Jewish diaspora]]\n| creator          = [[Ancient Israelites]]\n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cake]]\n| served           = Room temperature\n| main_ingredient  = Cake base, [[Honey]]\n| variations       = [[Basbousa]], honey date cake, [[Jewish apple cake]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Lekach''' is a [[honey]]-sweetened [[cake]] made by [[Jews]], especially for the [[Jewish holiday]] of [[Rosh Hashanah]]. Known in [[Hebrew]] as ''\u02bfougat dvash'' (literally, honey cake) the word ''lekach'' is [[Yiddish]], perhaps from the [[Aramaic]], ''l\u0115khakh,'' meaning to mix thoroughly. Lekach is one of the symbolically significant foods traditionally eaten by [[Ashkenazi Jews]] at Rosh Hashanah in hopes of ensuring a sweet New Year.<ref name=\"zeldes\">{{Cite web | last = Zeldes | first = Leah A. | authorlink =  | title = Eat this! Lekach: Jewish honey cake, for a sweet new year  | work = Dining Chicago | publisher = Chicago's Restaurant & Entertainment Guide, Inc.  | date = September 16, 2009 | url = http://blog.diningchicago.com/2009/09/16/eat-this-lekach-jewish-honey-cake-for-new-year/ | format =  | doi =   | accessdate = October 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Jewish tradition of honeyed cakes may date back to [[basbousa]] (sometimes spelled basboosa), an ancient cake dating back to the time of the [[The Exodus|exodus]] in Egypt,<ref name=\"zeldes\" /> variations of which are still enjoyed throughout the [[Middle East]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Distributing lekach.jpg|thumb|right|[[Haredim]] in [[Bat Yam]], [[Israel]] giving lekach to members of the community prior to [[Yok Kippur]] in exchange for a donation to charity, a tradition started by the [[Lubavitcher Rebbe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Put a piece of Lekach in every envelope |url=https://collive.com/put-a-piece-of-lekach-in-every-envelope/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |agency=COL Live}}</ref>]]\n\nA very traditional honey cake from the [[Austrian Jews|Jewish community]] of Austria contains an equal weight of white rye flour and dark honey, strong coffee instead of water, cloves, cinnamon, allspice, and golden raisins in the loaf, with slivered almonds on top of the loaf. It also has a fair number of eggs, vegetable oil (usually corn oil), salt, and baking powder.\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Honey Cake prep.jpg|thumb|right|Lekach prior to baking.]]\nRecipes vary widely.  Lekach is usually a dense, loaf-shaped cake, but some versions are similar to [[sponge cake]] or [[pound cake]], with the addition of honey and spices, sometimes with coffee or tea for coloring. Other versions are more like [[gingerbread]], [[pain d'\u00e9pices]], or [[lebkuchen]].<ref name=\"zeldes\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cuisine]]\n*[[Tishpishti]]\n*[[Jewish apple cake]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Jewish cuisine}}\n{{Cuisine of Israel}}\n{{Cakes}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Israeli cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish desserts]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Cakes]]\n\n\n{{dessert-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cuisine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Lekach(Lekakh)\n| image            = Honey Cake.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Jewish honey cake, honey cake\n| country          = {{flag|Israel}}\n| region           = [[Jewish diaspora]]\n| creator          = [[Ancient Israelites]]\n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cake]]\n| served           = Room temperature\n| main_ingredient  = Cake base, [[Honey]]\n| variations       = [[Basbousa]], honey date cake, [[Jewish apple cake]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Lekach''' is a [[honey]]-sweetened [[cake]] made by [[Jews]], especially for the [[Jewish holiday]] of [[Rosh Hashanah]]. Known in [[Hebrew]] as ''\u02bfougat dvash'' (literally, honey cake) the word ''lekach'' is [[Yiddish]], perhaps from the [[Aramaic]], ''l\u0115khakh,'' meaning to mix thoroughly. Lekach is one of the symbolically significant foods traditionally eaten by [[Ashkenazi Jews]] at Rosh Hashanah in hopes of ensuring a sweet New Year.<ref name=\"zeldes\">{{Cite web | last = Zeldes | first = Leah A. | authorlink =  | title = Eat this! Lekach: Jewish honey cake, for a sweet new year  | work = Dining Chicago | publisher = Chicago's Restaurant & Entertainment Guide, Inc.  | date = September 16, 2009 | url = http://blog.diningchicago.com/2009/09/16/eat-this-lekach-jewish-honey-cake-for-new-year/ | format =  | doi =   | accessdate = October 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Jewish tradition of honeyed cakes may date back to [[basbousa]] (sometimes spelled basboosa), an ancient cake dating back to the time of the [[exodus]] in Egypt,<ref name=\"zeldes\" /> variations of which are still enjoyed throughout the [[Middle East]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Distributing lekach.jpg|thumb|right|[[Haredim]] in [[Bat Yam]], [[Israel]] giving lekach to members of the community prior to [[Yok Kippur]] in exchange for a donation to charity, a tradition started by the [[Lubavitcher Rebbe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Put a piece of Lekach in every envelope |url=https://collive.com/put-a-piece-of-lekach-in-every-envelope/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |agency=COL Live}}</ref>]]\n\nA very traditional honey cake from the [[Austrian Jews|Jewish community]] of Austria contains an equal weight of white rye flour and dark honey, strong coffee instead of water, cloves, cinnamon, allspice, and golden raisins in the loaf, with slivered almonds on top of the loaf. It also has a fair number of eggs, vegetable oil (usually corn oil), salt, and baking powder.\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Honey Cake prep.jpg|thumb|right|Lekach prior to baking.]]\nRecipes vary widely.  Lekach is usually a dense, loaf-shaped cake, but some versions are similar to [[sponge cake]] or [[pound cake]], with the addition of honey and spices, sometimes with coffee or tea for coloring. Other versions are more like [[gingerbread]], [[pain d'\u00e9pices]], or [[lebkuchen]].<ref name=\"zeldes\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cuisine]]\n*[[Tishpishti]]\n*[[Jewish apple cake]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Jewish cuisine}}\n{{Cuisine of Israel}}\n{{Cakes}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Israeli cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish desserts]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Cakes]]\n\n\n{{dessert-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cuisine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toExodus(link changed toThe Exodus) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lekach"}
{"title_page": "Jayne County", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actress and record producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jayne County\n| image            = Jayne County 2 by David Shankbone.JPG\n| alt              = \n| caption          = County at the premi\u00e8re of ''Squeezebox!'' at the 2008 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| image_size       = 220\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name   = Wayne Rogers\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1947|07|13}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dallas, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Proto-punk]]\n* [[glam punk]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n* [[boogie-woogie]]<ref name=\"Punk77\">{{cite web|title=Wayne County \u2013 Singles|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/groups/waynecountydiscography.htm|publisher=Punk77|accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> \n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* actress\n* DJ\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* harmonica\n* percussion\n}}\n| years_active     = \n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Safari Records|Safari]]\n* Attic\n* Revolver\n* [[Jungle Records|Jungle]]\n* ESP\n* Royalty\n* Fang\n* Ratcage\n* Munster\n* Poptown\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* Queen Elizabeth\n* [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]]\n* Jayne County & the Electrick Queers\n* Jayne County & the JC5\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.jaynecounty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jayne Rogers''', (born Wayne Rogers July 13, 1947), better known by her stage name '''Jayne County''' is an American singer, songwriter, actress and record producer whose career has spanned six decades. Under the name '''Wayne County''' (inspired by [[Wayne County, Michigan]]), she was the vocalist of influential [[proto-punk]] band [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]] who became known for their [[camp (style)|camp]]y and foul-mouthed [[ballad]]s, [[glam punk]] inspired songs, and image which was heavily influenced by [[Jackie Curtis]] and the [[Theatre of the Ridiculous]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} County in particular was known for her outrageous and unpredictable stage antics as well as possessing a distinctive singing voice. She went on to become rock's first openly [[transgender]] singer, and adopted the stage name Jayne County.\n\nCounty's music has encompassed a number of styles over the course of her career, including [[glam punk]], [[punk rock]], [[blues rock]], and [[boogie-woogie]].<ref name=\"Punk77\"/> County did not think her birth name Wayne Rogers \"sounded very glamorous\" and decided to adopt the name of the county in which [[Detroit]] was located because she admired bands from that city \"like [[Iggy Pop|Iggy [Pop]]] and all those people.\"<ref>{{cite video|first=Steve|last=Zehentner|title=Jayne County, The Lower East Side Biography Project, excerpt from 28 minute biography|url=https://vimeo.com/60910075|publisher=Vimeo|time=00:15}}</ref> Though she has never been a commercial success, she has been an influence on a number of musicians including [[David Bowie]], [[the Ramones]], [[Patti Smith]], [[Pete Burns]] and [[Lou Reed]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BV6SnnkAU9IC&pg=PA122&lpg=PA122&dq=jayne+county+influenced+lou+reed&source=bl&ots=ZtoLsOC3g2&sig=SPtSRipIwheFe01Z9qw7PkMn6rY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAWoVChMIq_mEkOf6xwIVQ3o-Ch0pwA11#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20influenced%20lou%20reed&f=false|title=Performing Glam Rock: Gender and Theatricality in Popular Music|author=Auslander, Philip|date=2006|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> and many of County's songs have become well-known, including \"Are You Man Enough to Be a Woman\", \"[[Fuck Off (song)|Fuck Off]]\", \"Stuck on You,\" and \"Night Time\". Pianist [[Jools Holland]]'s first studio outing was with County on her single \"Fuck Off\". She also appeared as an actress at [[Andy Warhol]]'s [[The Factory|Factory]] and had a brief association with [[David Bowie]] during the 1970s. County played 'Lounge Lizard\" in the first punk rock film, [[Derek Jarman]]'s ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]'', and the band performed \"Paranoia Paradise\",<ref name=\"Johnson Interview\"/> which also appeared on the Jubilee Soundtrack album, released by Polydor UK in 1978. Wayne County and the Electric Chairs were supported by [[The Police]] during their 1977 tour of Holland,<ref name=\"Historia\">Sutcliffe, Phil & Fielder, Hugh (1981). ''L'Historia Bandido''. London and New York: Proteus Books. {{ISBN|0-906071-66-6}}. Pages 42 and 54.</ref> later recruiting Police guitarist [[Henry Padovani]] on rhythm guitar.<ref name=\"Padovani90\">{{cite book|last=Padovani |first=Henry |title=Secret Police Man|date=2009|publisher=Pen Press|isbn=978-1-907172-83-0 |pages=90\u201397}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in 1947, County left her hometown of [[Dallas, Georgia]], in 1968 at 19 years old to move to<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernadicou |first1=August |title=Jayne County |url=https://www.augustnation.com/jayne-county |website=August Nation |publisher=The LGBTQ History Project |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> [[New York City]], where she became a regular at the [[Stonewall Inn]] and took part in the [[Stonewall riots|historic riots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dangerousminds.net/comments/why_was_transgender_punk_icon_jayne_county_banned_from_facebook|title=Why was transgender punk idon Jayne County banned from Facebook?|website=Dangerousminds.net|date=23 April 2014|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> In 1969 County was asked by [[Warhol superstars|Warhol superstar]] and playwright [[Jackie Curtis]] to appear in her play, ''Femme Fatale''. The play had a successful run at [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]] and also starred [[Patti Smith]]. In her autobiography, County says of Curtis, \"She was my biggest influence, the person who really got me started.\"<ref name=biography>{{cite book|title=Man Enough to Be a Woman''|first=Jayne|last=County|first2=Rupert|last2=Smith|date=1995|publisher=Serpents's Tail|ISBN=1-85242-338-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/manenoughtobewom00coun}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===1970\u20131979===\nAfter appearing in ''Femme Fatale'', County wrote the play ''World \u2013 Birth of a Nation (The Castration of Man)''. The play was directed by [[Anthony Ingrassia|Tony Ingrassia]] and promoted as a \"homosexual fantasy.\" The play was set in a hospital and related to castration of the male sex. County played both Florence Nitingale and her sister Ethel Nitingale, and the play also featured [[Cherry Vanilla]] who played a nurse named Tilly Tons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaynecounty.com/#!world---a-birth-of-a-nation/c1eny|title=World \u2013 Birth of a Nation|website=Jaynecounty.com|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter seeing County in the play, Warhol cast her in his own theatrical production of ''Pork'', which was also adapted and directed by Tony Ingrassia.<ref>{{cite web|last = Lalumia |first = Jimi | title = Wayne County At The Trucks|website=Punkglobe.com | url =http://www.punkglobe.com/waynecountytrucksreview.html}}</ref> After a run in New York, the play was performed in [[London]] with the same New York cast. Upon returning to New York, County appeared in another play, ''Island'' by [[Anthony Ingrassia|Tony Ingrassia]], again with Patti Smith.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbHeAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=jayne+county+tony+ingrassia+island&source=bl&ots=XfFXbN_BQb&sig=iPagXqtm4ySblbZphAUI3121meg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAmoVChMI_4e60tn6xwIVBBU-Ch09ugUH#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20tony%20ingrassia%20island&f=false|title=Please Kill Me: The Uncensored Oral History of Punk|date=1996|first=Legs|last=McNeil|first2=Gillian|last2=McCain|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 County formed ''Queen Elizabeth'', one of the pioneering [[proto-punk]] bands. County was signed to MainMan Artistes, [[David Bowie]]'s management firm, but no records were ever produced. The company spent over $200,000 to film the 1974 stage show, \"Wayne at the Trucks\", but footage has never been released. The show featured numerous costume changes and some of County's raunchiest material. Eight songs from the show were released on the 2006 album, ''Wayne County At the Trucks'', on Munster Records. County claims the show was the inspiration for Bowie's ''[[Diamond Dogs]]'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Katrina|url=http://www.katrinafox.com/jaynecounty.htm |title=Complete and Utter County |work=SX News |date=August 24, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905194411/http://www.katrinafox.com/jaynecounty.htm|archivedate=September 5, 2006}}</ref> In particular, County maintains that the song \"Queenage Baby\" was a prototype for Bowie's song \"[[Rebel Rebel]]\", a claim which is supported by some rock critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punkglobe.com/waynecountytrucksreview.html |title=Punk Globe Magazine Online |publisher=Punkglobe.com |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Dave \n  | title = Wayne County At The Trucks- Review|website=[[AllMusic]]\n  | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r862715|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974 County formed Wayne County and the Backstreet Boys, which recorded three tracks for ''Max's Kansas City: New York New Wave'', a compilation that also featured [[Suicide (band)|Suicide]], [[Pere Ubu]], [[Cherry Vanilla]] and [[Man 2 Man|The Fast]]. Wayne County and The Backstreet Boys played regularly at [[CBGB]] and [[Max's Kansas City]], where County was also a DJ. In 1976, she appeared in the film ''[[The Blank Generation]]'', directed by [[Amos Poe]] and [[Ivan Kral]]. The film, the recording and the shows were the beginnings of what came to be known as [[punk rock]], and helped define the movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americanstudies.nd.edu/assets/91769/finney_thesis.pdf|title=A Blank Generation: Richard Hell and American Punk Rock|website=Americanstudies.nd.edu|author=Finney, Ross|date=2012|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 County moved to London, where the English punk scene was just emerging, and formed [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]]. County released the [[extended play|EP]] ''Electric Chairs 1977'', plus a [[single (music)|single]] on [[Illegal Records]]. This was followed by \"Fuck Off\", recorded as a single for [[Safari Records]] and supported with a European tour. While in London, County met [[Derek Jarman]], who cast her as \"Lounge Lizard\" in the seminal punk film ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]'', which also starred [[Adam Ant]], [[Toyah Willcox]], [[Ian Charleson]], [[Nell Campbell|Little Nell]] and [[Pamela Rooke|Jordan]].<ref name=enc>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA2006-IA1449&lpg=PA2006-IA1449&dq=jayne+county+jubilee&source=bl&ots=JboPwq1cZt&sig=KrzhqUUGymDrJjfNZ-A52c1CqHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBGoVChMIyIbguuH6xwIVSYI-Ch3bhAYc#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20jubilee&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|author=Larkin, Colin|publisher=Omnibus|date=2007|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> County and band are also featured in ''[[The Punk Rock Movie]]'', by [[Don Letts]], containing part of a 1977 performance at [[The Roxy (Covent Garden)|The Roxy]] club in London.\n\nIn 1978, the Wayne County song \"Fucked by the Devil,\" was recorded by Jimi LaLumia and The Psychotic Frogs. The song was released on Jimi LaLumia and The Psychotic Frogs' EP Typically Tasteless. It was a vinyl EP that instantly sold 10,000 copies. Later on Jimi LaLumia would work with Wayne County in a managerial position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicrockhistory.com/jimi-lalumia-the-psychotic-frogs-impact-on-the-70s-punk-scene/|title=Jimi LaLumia & The Psychotic Frogs' Impact On The 70's Punk Scene|last=Scavieli|first=Tony|date=2017|archive-url=http://www.classicrockhistory.com/jimi-lalumia-the-psychotic-frogs-impact-on-the-70s-punk-scene|archive-date=3 July 2017|url-status=|access-date=30 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after this, Wayne County and The Electric Chairs recorded their first, [[eponym]]ous album, as well as another EP, ''Blatantly Offensive'', which contained \"Fuck Off\" and \"Toilet Love.\" After their touring in support of these releases was done, they recorded ''Storm the Gates of Heaven''. Their next album, released in 1979, was ''Things Your Mother Never Told You'', which featured several songs based on County's experiences in Germany. The album was produced by [[David Cunningham (musician)|David Cunningham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/things-your-mother-never-told-you-mw0000837906|title=Jayne County & the Electric Chairs: Things Your Mother Never Told You|author=Thompson, Dave|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> After it was released, the band broke up and County, along with guitarist Eliot Michaels, returned to the U.S.\n\nWhen County moved to Berlin in 1979, she changed her stage name to \"Jayne County\",<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TdSJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220&lpg=PA220&dq=jayne+county+born&source=bl&ots=-PcVE5MUGT&sig=XxeWQp9QdVhPbFKfeenw8kD8ams&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CHAQ6AEwEGoVChMI0cCZh9b6xwIVwnI-Ch2U7g55#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20born&f=false|title=The Queer Encyclopedia of Music, Dance, & Musical Theater|author=Summers, Claude J.|date=2004|publisher=Cleis|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> publicly identifying as a woman for the first time. County's release of ''Rock and Roll Resurrection (In Concert)'' on [[Safari Records]], was under this new name. The first live show under County's new name in Toronto, Canada, sparked erroneous rumors of a sex change operation.<ref name=enc />\n\n===1980\u2013present===\nIn 1983 County returned to New York where she appeared in the theatrical production ''Les Girls'' with [[Holly Woodlawn]]. Shortly thereafter she returned to London for the premi\u00e8re of ''City of Lost Souls'' and stayed long enough to record and tour another album, ''[[Private Oyster]]'', with Warren Heighway as manager. Her band included members of various UK based rock bands, including [[Manchester]]-based guitarists, Stu Clarke and Chris Lynch [Rockson], Mark Pearson on bass and Bazz Creece on drums.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHP-r9-eqdAC&pg=PA289&lpg=PA289&dq=jayne+county+private+oyster+tour&source=bl&ots=nILuQakw0M&sig=cM7dFlQEAdv4_U--5nJPJMDt0zA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDsQ6AEwB2oVChMI0pb2zNv6xwIVwoI-Ch2GlQH1#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20private%20oyster%20tour&f=false|date=2000|publisher=Miller Freeman|title=Alternative Rock|author=Thompson, Dave|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> Following widespread media attention, she returned to the U.S., where her manager for America, Jimi LaLumia, secured the release of the album \"Goddess Of Wet Dreams\" on the ESP DISK label; this became County's first U.S. release.Lalumia then secured a deal for County with the NY based label Royalty Records; Royalty released the UK based County compilation \"Rock And Roll Cleopatra\", and the subsequent studio album, \"Deviation\"; Royalty launched County's first and only major U.S. tour in support of the releases.     \n\nFrom 1990 onwards many of County's earlier recordings were re-released, including the early Safari tracks, on a CD called ''Rock & Roll Cleopatra''. She recorded the album ''Goddess of Wet Dreams'' in 1993, followed by ''[[Deviation (Jayne County album)|Deviation]]'' in 1995. Later that year, she appeared in ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]'' and released her autobiography, ''Man Enough to Be a Woman''.<ref name=\"biography\" /> From 1989\u20131997, Jayne County & The Electric Chairs consisted of Jayne on vocals, Mark Pearson on bass, Paul Wainwright on guitar, and Colin Rocks on drums. This lineup recorded and toured the UK and Europe during this time.     \n    \nSince that time several new tracks have surfaced on various compilations and through County's official website. Many of these tracks, both live and studio recordings, were collected on the Ratcage Records release ''So New York'', including collaborations with Lisa Jackson and former Electric Chairs guitarist Eliot Michaels. A live show, recorded on County's birthday, was released on the 2002 CD ''Wash Me in the Blood (of Rock & Roll)- Live at Squeeze Box'' by Fang Records.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wash-me-in-the-blood-of-rock-and-roll-mw0000995517|title=Wash me in the blood of rock and roll|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Mason, Stewart|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> The CD features a duet on \"California Sun\" by County and former nemesis [[Richard Manitoba|\"Handsome\" Dick Manitoba]] of [[The Dictators]].\n\nAfter leaving New York City, County settled in the Atlanta area where she has a band called the Electrick Queers with guitarist Jet Terror, bassist Gary Yoxen, and drummer Rob Kirkland. In 2014 she released a DVD of ''Wayne/Jayne County and The Electric Chairs, Live in Germany'' from 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/10/jayne-county-after-dark_n_5662717.html|author=Nichols, JamesMichael|title=After Dark: Jayne County, Transgender Musician And Nightlife Icon|website=Huffingtonpost.com|date=10 August 2014|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> On July 22, 2015, Jayne County & the Electrick Queers headlined ARMageddon, to benefit Blast-Off Burlesque's Trey Chic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clatl.com/cribnotes/archives/2015/07/21/jayne-county-and-the-electrick-queers-bring-armageddon-to-the-earl|title=Jayne County & the Electrick Queers bring ARMageddon to the Earl|website=Clatl.com|author=Williams, Jonathan|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 2017, County released a five-track extended play download by Jayne County and The JC5 entitled \"Here Come The JC5\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaynecounty.com/news%2016%20-%2018.html|title=NEWS 2016 - 2018|website=Jaynecounty.com|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, County debuted a retrospective show of visual art at Participant, Inc, a gallery in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/interviews/jayne-county-talks-about-her-retrospective-at-participant-inc-in-new-york-74357|title=Interviews: Jayne County|last=Fialho|first=Alex|date=February 19, 2018|website=Artforum.com|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Comprising five decades of work, ''Paranoia Paradise'' included paintings, drawings, collages, and photography.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/428495/jayne-county-participant-inc/|title=The Outrageous Art of Transgender Punk Rock Star Jayne County|date=2018-02-21|website=Hyperallergic.com|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nJayne County is enjoying a renewed recording career  with the success of anti animal experimentation  single \"Leave My Pu**y Alone\"  and the trans anthem \"IGenderTy\".\n\n==Works==\n\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director(s)\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''Night Lunch''\n| [[Ivan Kral]] and [[Amos Poe]]\n|-\n| 1976 \n| ''[[The Blank Generation]]''\n| Ivan Kral and Amos Poe\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''Punk in London''\n| Wolfgang B\u00fcld\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Punk Rock Movie]]''\n| [[Don Letts]]\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]''\n| [[Derek Jarman]]\n|- \n| 1982\n| ''Stadt der verlorenen Seelen (City of Lost Souls)''\n| [[Rosa von Praunheim]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]''\n| Barry Shils\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Born to Lose: The Last Rock and Roll Movie''\n| [[Lech Kowalski]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Freaks, Glam Gods and Rock Stars''\n| Tim Ryan\n|- \n| 2003\n| ''End of the Century''\n| Jim Fields and Michael Gramaglia\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[King of Punk]]''\n| Kenneth van Schooten\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Squeezebox!''\n| Steven Saporito and Zach Shaffer\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Burning Down the House: The Story of CBGB''\n| Mandy Stein\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Beautiful Darling]]''\n| James Rasin\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Jobriath A.D.''\n| Kieran Turner\n|-\n<!-- Per WP:CRYSTAL and WP:NFF, DO NOT add films not yet in production\" (\"In pre-production\"). -->\n|}\n\n===Discography===\n;Albums\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Label\n|-\n| 1978 || ''The Electric Chairs'' || [[Safari Records|Safari]]\n|-\n| 1978 || ''Storm the Gates of Heaven'' || Safari\n|-\n| 1979 || ''Things Your Mother Never Told You'' || Safari\n|-\n| 1980 || ''Rock and Roll Resurrection (In Concert)'' || Safari/Attic Records Li\n|-\n| 1982 || Best Of Jayne/Wayne County And The Electric Chairs || Safari \n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Private Oyster]]'' || Revolver\n|-\n| 1989 || ''Betty Grable's Legs'' || [[Jungle Records|Jungle]]\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Goddess of Wet Dreams'' || ESP\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Deviation (Jayne County album)|Deviation]]'' || Royalty\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Wash Me in the Blood (of Rock & Roll)- Live at Squeeze Box'' || Fang\n|-\n| 2003 || ''So New York'' || Ratcage\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Wayne County at the Trucks'' || Munster\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Goddess Of Wet Dreams-The Legacy Edition'' || MVD\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Amerikan Cleopatra/Private Oyster-The Legacy Edition'' || MVD\n|}\n\n;Extended plays\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Label\n|-\n| 1976 || ''Max's Kansas City 1976'' || Ram Stereo 1213\n|-\n| 1977 || ''The Electric Chairs'' || [[Illegal Records|Illegal]]\n|-\n| 1978 || ''Blatantly Offensive'' || Safari\n|-\n| 2017 || ''Here Come The JC5'' || Adrastea Music\n|}\n\n;Singles\n*\"Twist and Shout\"/\"Boys\" with Jimi LaLumia & The Psychotic Frogs/also featuring Johnny Thunders and Cherry Vanilla-Beat This Label-1981\n*\"Razor Clam\", (with She Wolves), Poptown Records 2007''\n*\"California Uber Alles\", (with She Wolves), Poptown Records 2007\n*\"Hail Satan!\", (with Sharon Needles), Independent 2013\n*\"Leave My Pu**y Alone\", (with Jimi LaLumia), LaLumia Tunes 2017\n* \"IGenderTy\",LaLumia Tunes 2018\n\n===Biography===\n*''Man Enough to Be a Woman'', Jayne County with Rupert Smith, 1995, published by Serpents's Tail {{ISBN|1-85242-338-2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.jaynecounty.com/}}\n* {{Allmusic |id= mn0000224658}}\n* {{IMDb name|0183629}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    ======================= {{No more links}} =============================-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:County, Jayne}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual DJs]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock percussionists]]\n[[Category:American punk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas, Georgia]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Protopunk musicians]]\n[[Category:Blues rock musicians]]\n[[Category:ESP-Disk artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:People associated with The Factory]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women record producers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actress and record producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jayne County\n| image            = Jayne County 2 by David Shankbone.JPG\n| alt              = \n| caption          = County at the premi\u00e8re of ''Squeezebox!'' at the 2008 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| image_size       = 220\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name   = Wayne Rogers\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1947|07|13}}\n| birth_place      = [[Dallas, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Proto-punk]]\n* [[glam punk]]\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n* [[boogie-woogie]]<ref name=\"Punk77\">{{cite web|title=Wayne County \u2013 Singles|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/groups/waynecountydiscography.htm|publisher=Punk77|accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> \n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* actress\n* DJ\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* harmonica\n* percussion\n}}\n| years_active     = \n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Safari Records|Safari]]\n* Attic\n* Revolver\n* [[Jungle Records|Jungle]]\n* ESP\n* Royalty\n* Fang\n* Ratcage\n* Munster\n* Poptown\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* Queen Elizabeth\n* [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]]\n* Jayne County & the Electrick Queers\n* Jayne County & the JC5\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.jaynecounty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jayne Rogers''', (born Wayne Rogers July 13, 1947), better known by her stage name '''Jayne County''' is an American singer, songwriter, actress and record producer whose career has spanned six decades. Under the name '''Wayne County''' (inspired by [[Wayne County, Michigan]]), she was the vocalist of influential [[proto-punk]] band [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]] who became known for their [[camp (style)|camp]]y and foul-mouthed [[ballad]]s, [[glam punk]] inspired songs, and image which was heavily influenced by [[Jackie Curtis]] and the [[Theatre of the Ridiculous]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} County in particular was known for her outrageous and unpredictable stage antics as well as possessing a distinctive singing voice. She went on to become rock's first openly [[transgender]] singer, and adopted the stage name Jayne County.\n\nCounty's music has encompassed a number of styles over the course of her career, including [[glam punk]], [[punk rock]], [[blues rock]], and [[boogie-woogie]].<ref name=\"Punk77\"/> County did not think her birth name Wayne Rogers \"sounded very glamorous\" and decided to adopt the name of the county in which [[Detroit]] was located because she admired bands from that city \"like [[Iggy Pop|Iggy [Pop]]] and all those people.\"<ref>{{cite video|first=Steve|last=Zehentner|title=Jayne County, The Lower East Side Biography Project, excerpt from 28 minute biography|url=https://vimeo.com/60910075|publisher=Vimeo|time=00:15}}</ref> Though she has never been a commercial success, she has been an influence on a number of musicians including [[David Bowie]], [[the Ramones]], [[Patti Smith]], [[Pete Burns]] and [[Lou Reed]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BV6SnnkAU9IC&pg=PA122&lpg=PA122&dq=jayne+county+influenced+lou+reed&source=bl&ots=ZtoLsOC3g2&sig=SPtSRipIwheFe01Z9qw7PkMn6rY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAWoVChMIq_mEkOf6xwIVQ3o-Ch0pwA11#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20influenced%20lou%20reed&f=false|title=Performing Glam Rock: Gender and Theatricality in Popular Music|author=Auslander, Philip|date=2006|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> and many of County's songs have become well-known, including \"Are You Man Enough to Be a Woman\", \"[[Fuck Off (song)|Fuck Off]]\", \"Stuck on You,\" and \"Night Time\". Pianist [[Jools Holland]]'s first studio outing was with County on her single \"Fuck Off\". She also appeared as an actress at [[Andy Warhol]]'s [[The Factory|Factory]] and had a brief association with [[David Bowie]] during the 1970's. County played 'Lounge Lizard\" in the first punk rock film, [[Derek Jarman]]'s ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]'', and the band performed \"Paranoia Paradise\",<ref name=\"Johnson Interview\"/> which also appeared on the Jubilee Soundtrack album, released by Polydor UK in 1978. Wayne County and the Electric Chairs were supported by [[The Police]] during their 1977 tour of Holland,<ref name=\"Historia\">Sutcliffe, Phil & Fielder, Hugh (1981). ''L'Historia Bandido''. London and New York: Proteus Books. {{ISBN|0-906071-66-6}}. Pages 42 and 54.</ref> later recruiting Police guitarist [[Henry Padovani]] on rhythm guitar.<ref name=\"Padovani90\">{{cite book|last=Padovani |first=Henry |title=Secret Police Man|date=2009|publisher=Pen Press|isbn=978-1-907172-83-0 |pages=90\u201397}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in 1947, County left her hometown of [[Dallas, Georgia]], in 1968 at 19 years old to move to<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernadicou |first1=August |title=Jayne County |url=https://www.augustnation.com/jayne-county |website=August Nation |publisher=The LGBTQ History Project |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> [[New York City]], where she became a regular at the [[Stonewall Inn]] and took part in the [[Stonewall riots|historic riots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dangerousminds.net/comments/why_was_transgender_punk_icon_jayne_county_banned_from_facebook|title=Why was transgender punk idon Jayne County banned from Facebook?|website=Dangerousminds.net|date=23 April 2014|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> In 1969 County was asked by [[Warhol superstars|Warhol superstar]] and playwright [[Jackie Curtis]] to appear in her play, ''Femme Fatale''. The play had a successful run at [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]] and also starred [[Patti Smith]]. In her autobiography, County says of Curtis, \"She was my biggest influence, the person who really got me started.\"<ref name=biography>{{cite book|title=Man Enough to Be a Woman''|first=Jayne|last=County|first2=Rupert|last2=Smith|date=1995|publisher=Serpents's Tail|ISBN=1-85242-338-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/manenoughtobewom00coun}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===1970\u20131979===\nAfter appearing in ''Femme Fatale'', County wrote the play ''World \u2013 Birth of a Nation (The Castration of Man)''. The play was directed by [[Anthony Ingrassia|Tony Ingrassia]] and promoted as a \"homosexual fantasy.\" The play was set in a hospital and related to castration of the male sex. County played both Florence Nitingale and her sister Ethel Nitingale, and the play also featured [[Cherry Vanilla]] who played a nurse named Tilly Tons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaynecounty.com/#!world---a-birth-of-a-nation/c1eny|title=World \u2013 Birth of a Nation|website=Jaynecounty.com|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter seeing County in the play, Warhol cast her in his own theatrical production of ''Pork'', which was also adapted and directed by Tony Ingrassia.<ref>{{cite web|last = Lalumia |first = Jimi | title = Wayne County At The Trucks|website=Punkglobe.com | url =http://www.punkglobe.com/waynecountytrucksreview.html}}</ref> After a run in New York, the play was performed in [[London]] with the same New York cast. Upon returning to New York, County appeared in another play, ''Island'' by [[Anthony Ingrassia|Tony Ingrassia]], again with Patti Smith.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbHeAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=jayne+county+tony+ingrassia+island&source=bl&ots=XfFXbN_BQb&sig=iPagXqtm4ySblbZphAUI3121meg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAmoVChMI_4e60tn6xwIVBBU-Ch09ugUH#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20tony%20ingrassia%20island&f=false|title=Please Kill Me: The Uncensored Oral History of Punk|date=1996|first=Legs|last=McNeil|first2=Gillian|last2=McCain|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 County formed ''Queen Elizabeth'', one of the pioneering [[proto-punk]] bands. County was signed to MainMan Artistes, [[David Bowie]]'s management firm, but no records were ever produced. The company spent over $200,000 to film the 1974 stage show, \"Wayne at the Trucks\", but footage has never been released. The show featured numerous costume changes and some of County's raunchiest material. Eight songs from the show were released on the 2006 album, ''Wayne County At the Trucks'', on Munster Records. County claims the show was the inspiration for Bowie's ''[[Diamond Dogs]]'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Katrina|url=http://www.katrinafox.com/jaynecounty.htm |title=Complete and Utter County |work=SX News |date=August 24, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905194411/http://www.katrinafox.com/jaynecounty.htm|archivedate=September 5, 2006}}</ref> In particular, County maintains that the song \"Queenage Baby\" was a prototype for Bowie's song \"[[Rebel Rebel]]\", a claim which is supported by some rock critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punkglobe.com/waynecountytrucksreview.html |title=Punk Globe Magazine Online |publisher=Punkglobe.com |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Dave \n  | title = Wayne County At The Trucks- Review|website=[[AllMusic]]\n  | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r862715|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974 County formed Wayne County and the Backstreet Boys, which recorded three tracks for ''Max's Kansas City: New York New Wave'', a compilation that also featured [[Suicide (band)|Suicide]], [[Pere Ubu]], [[Cherry Vanilla]] and [[Man 2 Man|The Fast]]. Wayne County and The Backstreet Boys played regularly at [[CBGB]] and [[Max's Kansas City]], where County was also a DJ. In 1976, she appeared in the film ''[[The Blank Generation]]'', directed by [[Amos Poe]] and [[Ivan Kral]]. The film, the recording and the shows were the beginnings of what came to be known as [[punk rock]], and helped define the movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americanstudies.nd.edu/assets/91769/finney_thesis.pdf|title=A Blank Generation: Richard Hell and American Punk Rock|website=Americanstudies.nd.edu|author=Finney, Ross|date=2012|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 County moved to London, where the English punk scene was just emerging, and formed [[Wayne County & the Electric Chairs]]. County released the [[extended play|EP]] ''Electric Chairs 1977'', plus a [[single (music)|single]] on [[Illegal Records]]. This was followed by \"Fuck Off\", recorded as a single for [[Safari Records]] and supported with a European tour. While in London, County met [[Derek Jarman]], who cast her as \"Lounge Lizard\" in the seminal punk film ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]'', which also starred [[Adam Ant]], [[Toyah Willcox]], [[Ian Charleson]], [[Nell Campbell|Little Nell]] and [[Pamela Rooke|Jordan]].<ref name=enc>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA2006-IA1449&lpg=PA2006-IA1449&dq=jayne+county+jubilee&source=bl&ots=JboPwq1cZt&sig=KrzhqUUGymDrJjfNZ-A52c1CqHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBGoVChMIyIbguuH6xwIVSYI-Ch3bhAYc#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20jubilee&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|author=Larkin, Colin|publisher=Omnibus|date=2007|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> County and band are also featured in ''[[The Punk Rock Movie]]'', by [[Don Letts]], containing part of a 1977 performance at [[The Roxy (Covent Garden)|The Roxy]] club in London.\n\nIn 1978, the Wayne County song \"Fucked by the Devil,\" was recorded by Jimi LaLumia and The Psychotic Frogs. The song was released on Jimi LaLumia and The Psychotic Frogs' EP Typically Tasteless. It was a vinyl EP that instantly sold 10,000 copies. Later on Jimi LaLumia would work with Wayne County in a managerial position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicrockhistory.com/jimi-lalumia-the-psychotic-frogs-impact-on-the-70s-punk-scene/|title=Jimi LaLumia & The Psychotic Frogs' Impact On The 70's Punk Scene|last=Scavieli|first=Tony|date=2017|archive-url=http://www.classicrockhistory.com/jimi-lalumia-the-psychotic-frogs-impact-on-the-70s-punk-scene|archive-date=3 July 2017|url-status=|access-date=30 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after this, Wayne County and The Electric Chairs recorded their first, [[eponym]]ous album, as well as another EP, ''Blatantly Offensive'', which contained \"Fuck Off\" and \"Toilet Love.\" After their touring in support of these releases was done, they recorded ''Storm the Gates of Heaven''. Their next album, released in 1979, was ''Things Your Mother Never Told You'', which featured several songs based on County's experiences in Germany. The album was produced by [[David Cunningham (musician)|David Cunningham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/things-your-mother-never-told-you-mw0000837906|title=Jayne County & the Electric Chairs: Things Your Mother Never Told You|author=Thompson, Dave|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> After it was released, the band broke up and County, along with guitarist Eliot Michaels, returned to the U.S.\n\nWhen County moved to Berlin in 1979, she changed her stage name to \"Jayne County\",<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TdSJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220&lpg=PA220&dq=jayne+county+born&source=bl&ots=-PcVE5MUGT&sig=XxeWQp9QdVhPbFKfeenw8kD8ams&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CHAQ6AEwEGoVChMI0cCZh9b6xwIVwnI-Ch2U7g55#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20born&f=false|title=The Queer Encyclopedia of Music, Dance, & Musical Theater|author=Summers, Claude J.|date=2004|publisher=Cleis|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> publicly identifying as a woman for the first time. County's release of ''Rock and Roll Resurrection (In Concert)'' on [[Safari Records]], was under this new name. The first live show under County's new name in Toronto, Canada, sparked erroneous rumors of a sex change operation.<ref name=enc />\n\n===1980\u2013present===\nIn 1983 County returned to New York where she appeared in the theatrical production ''Les Girls'' with [[Holly Woodlawn]]. Shortly thereafter she returned to London for the premi\u00e8re of ''City of Lost Souls'' and stayed long enough to record and tour another album, ''[[Private Oyster]]'', with Warren Heighway as manager. Her band included members of various UK based rock bands, including [[Manchester]]-based guitarists, Stu Clarke and Chris Lynch [Rockson], Mark Pearson on bass and Bazz Creece on drums.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHP-r9-eqdAC&pg=PA289&lpg=PA289&dq=jayne+county+private+oyster+tour&source=bl&ots=nILuQakw0M&sig=cM7dFlQEAdv4_U--5nJPJMDt0zA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDsQ6AEwB2oVChMI0pb2zNv6xwIVwoI-Ch2GlQH1#v=onepage&q=jayne%20county%20private%20oyster%20tour&f=false|date=2000|publisher=Miller Freeman|title=Alternative Rock|author=Thompson, Dave|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> Following widespread media attention, she returned to the U.S., where her manager for America, Jimi LaLumia, secured the release of the album \"Goddess Of Wet Dreams\" on the ESP DISK label; this became County's first U.S. release.Lalumia then secured a deal for County with the NY based label Royalty Records; Royalty released the UK based County compilation \"Rock And Roll Cleopatra\", and the subsequent studio album, \"Deviation\"; Royalty launched County's first and only major U.S. tour in support of the releases.     \n\nFrom 1990 onwards many of County's earlier recordings were re-released, including the early Safari tracks, on a CD called ''Rock & Roll Cleopatra''. She recorded the album ''Goddess of Wet Dreams'' in 1993, followed by ''[[Deviation (Jayne County album)|Deviation]]'' in 1995. Later that year, she appeared in ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]'' and released her autobiography, ''Man Enough to Be a Woman''.<ref name=\"biography\" /> From 1989-1997, Jayne County & The Electric Chairs consisted of Jayne on vocals, Mark Pearson on bass, Paul Wainwright on guitar, and Colin Rocks on drums. This lineup recorded and toured the UK and Europe during this time.     \n    \nSince that time several new tracks have surfaced on various compilations and through County's official website. Many of these tracks, both live and studio recordings, were collected on the Ratcage Records release ''So New York'', including collaborations with Lisa Jackson and former Electric Chairs guitarist Eliot Michaels. A live show, recorded on County's birthday, was released on the 2002 CD ''Wash Me in the Blood (of Rock & Roll)- Live at Squeeze Box'' by Fang Records.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wash-me-in-the-blood-of-rock-and-roll-mw0000995517|title=Wash me in the blood of rock and roll|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Mason, Stewart|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> The CD features a duet on \"California Sun\" by County and former nemesis [[Richard Manitoba|\"Handsome\" Dick Manitoba]] of [[The Dictators]].\n\nAfter leaving New York City, County settled in the Atlanta area where she has a band called the Electrick Queers with guitarist Jet Terror, bassist Gary Yoxen, and drummer Rob Kirkland. In 2014 she released a DVD of ''Wayne/Jayne County and The Electric Chairs, Live in Germany'' from 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/10/jayne-county-after-dark_n_5662717.html|author=Nichols, JamesMichael|title=After Dark: Jayne County, Transgender Musician And Nightlife Icon|website=Huffingtonpost.com|date=10 August 2014|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> On July 22, 2015, Jayne County & the Electrick Queers headlined ARMageddon, to benefit Blast-Off Burlesque's Trey Chic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clatl.com/cribnotes/archives/2015/07/21/jayne-county-and-the-electrick-queers-bring-armageddon-to-the-earl|title=Jayne County & the Electrick Queers bring ARMageddon to the Earl|website=Clatl.com|author=Williams, Jonathan|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 2017, County released a five-track extended play download by Jayne County and The JC5 entitled \"Here Come The JC5\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaynecounty.com/news%2016%20-%2018.html|title=NEWS 2016 - 2018|website=Jaynecounty.com|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, County debuted a retrospective show of visual art at Participant, Inc, a gallery in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/interviews/jayne-county-talks-about-her-retrospective-at-participant-inc-in-new-york-74357|title=Interviews: Jayne County|last=Fialho|first=Alex|date=February 19, 2018|website=Artforum.com|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Comprising five decades of work, ''Paranoia Paradise'' included paintings, drawings, collages, and photography.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/428495/jayne-county-participant-inc/|title=The Outrageous Art of Transgender Punk Rock Star Jayne County|date=2018-02-21|website=Hyperallergic.com|access-date=2018-03-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nJayne County is enjoying a renewed recording career  with the success of anti animal experimentation  single \"Leave My Pu**y Alone\"  and the trans anthem \"IGenderTy\".\n\n==Works==\n\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director(s)\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''Night Lunch''\n| [[Ivan Kral]] and [[Amos Poe]]\n|-\n| 1976 \n| ''[[The Blank Generation]]''\n| Ivan Kral and Amos Poe\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''Punk in London''\n| Wolfgang B\u00fcld\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Punk Rock Movie]]''\n| [[Don Letts]]\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]]''\n| [[Derek Jarman]]\n|- \n| 1982\n| ''Stadt der verlorenen Seelen (City of Lost Souls)''\n| [[Rosa von Praunheim]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Wigstock: The Movie]]''\n| Barry Shils\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Born to Lose: The Last Rock and Roll Movie''\n| [[Lech Kowalski]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Freaks, Glam Gods and Rock Stars''\n| Tim Ryan\n|- \n| 2003\n| ''End of the Century''\n| Jim Fields and Michael Gramaglia\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[King of Punk]]''\n| Kenneth van Schooten\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Squeezebox!''\n| Steven Saporito and Zach Shaffer\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Burning Down the House: The Story of CBGB''\n| Mandy Stein\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Beautiful Darling]]''\n| James Rasin\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Jobriath A.D.''\n| Kieran Turner\n|-\n<!-- Per WP:CRYSTAL and WP:NFF, DO NOT add films not yet in production\" (\"In pre-production\"). -->\n|}\n\n===Discography===\n;Albums\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Label\n|-\n| 1978 || ''The Electric Chairs'' || [[Safari Records|Safari]]\n|-\n| 1978 || ''Storm the Gates of Heaven'' || Safari\n|-\n| 1979 || ''Things Your Mother Never Told You'' || Safari\n|-\n| 1980 || ''Rock and Roll Resurrection (In Concert)'' || Safari/Attic Records Li\n|-\n| 1982 || Best Of Jayne/Wayne County And The Electric Chairs || Safari \n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Private Oyster]]'' || Revolver\n|-\n| 1989 || ''Betty Grable's Legs'' || [[Jungle Records|Jungle]]\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Goddess of Wet Dreams'' || ESP\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Deviation (Jayne County album)|Deviation]]'' || Royalty\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Wash Me in the Blood (of Rock & Roll)- Live at Squeeze Box'' || Fang\n|-\n| 2003 || ''So New York'' || Ratcage\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Wayne County at the Trucks'' || Munster\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Goddess Of Wet Dreams-The Legacy Edition'' || MVD\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Amerikan Cleopatra/Private Oyster-The Legacy Edition'' || MVD\n|}\n\n;Extended plays\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\