{"title_page": "Thug Life", "text_new": "{{About|the hip hop group||Thug life (disambiguation){{!}}Thug life}}\n{{Short description|American hip hop group}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Thug Life\n| background = group_or_band\n| image = Thug Life.jpg\n| caption = From left to right: Big Syke, Mopreme, Tupac, Macadoshis, The Rated R.\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[G-funk]], [[gangsta rap]]\n| years_active = 1993\u20131995\n| label = [[Jive Records]], Out Da Gutta Records\n| associated_acts = \n| past_members = {{unbulleted list|[[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] (deceased)|[[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]] (deceased)|[[Big Syke]] (deceased)|[[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]]|Macadoshis|The Rated R}}\n}}\n\n'''Thug Life''' was an American [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] group that consisted of [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]], [[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]], [[Big Syke]], [[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]],  Macadoshis, and The Rated R. They released one album, 1994's ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'', before disbanding in 1995. \n\n==History==\n2Pac, Randy \"Stretch\" Walker and Princess Mel formed Thug Life in 1992 with Tyruss \"Little Psycho\" Himes.<ref name=allmusicbio>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p211189|pure_url=yes}} Big Syke bio] at [[Allmusic]]</ref> They recorded a song also titled, \"Thug Life\".  Soon Little Psycho joined the group, under the name Syke. Later Macadoshis and The Rated R joined the group. They signed with Interscope Records and recorded an LP titled ''Thug Life Volume 1''. Tupac's stepbrother, Mopreme Shakur, later joined the group.\n\n== ''Thug Life: Volume 1'' ==\nOn September 26, 1994, ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'' was released.\n\nThe first single and video was \"Pour Out a Little Liquor\" which was a Tupac solo song. \n\nTupac performed \"Out on Bail\" at the 1994 Source Awards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Busta Rhymes Says Tupac Dissing A Tribe Called Quest Was A Misunderstanding  |url=http://hiphopwired.com/2012/09/09/busta-rhymes-says-tupac-dissing-a-tribe-called-quest-was-a-misunderstanding-video/ |work=hiphopwired.com |publisher=Hip Hop Wired |date= 9 September 2012 |accessdate= 8 January 2016 |last=Aqua Blanco |first=Alvin}}</ref> The album was originally released on Shakur's label Out Da Gutta. Tupac's mother's label, [[Amaru Entertainment]], has since gained the rights to the album.\n\nThe track \"How Long Will They Mourn Me?\" appeared on 2Pac's 1998 ''Greatest Hits'' album.\n\n''Thug Life: Volume 1'' sold 478,419 copies in the United States as of 2011.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Stretch's death==\nOn November 30, 1995, Stretch died after being shot four times in the back by three men who pulled up alongside his minivan in Queens Village.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rapper Slain After Chase in Queens |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/01/nyregion/rapper-slain-after-chase-in-queens.html |work=nytimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date= 1 December 1995 |accessdate= 1 December 2012 |last=Jones |first=Charisse}}</ref> Stretch was killed exactly one year after 2Pac's 1994 Quad Studio shooting.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biggie, Diddy Knew Tupac Would Be Ambushed In 1994, Alleges Los Angeles Times Reporter |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1583487/biggie-diddy-knew-tupac-would-be-ambushed-in-1994-alleges-los-angeles-times-reporter/ |work=mtv.com |publisher=MTV |date= 16 March 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2016 |last=Reid |first=Shaheem}}</ref>\n\n==Original members==\n* [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] ({{aka}} Makaveli) ({{abbr|d.|died}} 1996)\n* [[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]] (a.k.a. Big Stretch) (d. 1995)\n* [[Big Syke]] (a.k.a. Mussolini or Little Psycho) (d. 2016)\n* [[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]] (a.k.a. Mocedes, The Wycked, Komani or Mo' Khomani)\n* Macadoshis (a.k.a. The Original Mac 10)\n* The Rated R (a.k.a. Super Star)\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'' (1994)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Tupac Shakur}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Music|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:African-American musical groups]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rap groups]]\n[[Category:G-funk groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Jive Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the hip hop group||Thug life (disambiguation){{!}}Thug life}}\n{{Short description|American hip hop group}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Thug Life\n| background = group_or_band\n| image = Thug Life.jpg\n| caption = From left to right: Big Syke, Mopreme, Tupac, Macadoshis, The Rated R.\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[G-funk]], [[gangsta rap]]\n| years_active = 1993\u20131995\n| label = [[Jive Records]], Out Da Gutta Records\n| associated_acts = \n| past_members = {{unbulleted list|[[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] (deceased)|[[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]] (deceased)|[[Big Syke]] (deceased)|[[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]]|Macadoshis|The Rated R}}\n}}\n\n'''Thug Life''' was an American [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] group that consisted of [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]], [[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]], [[Big Syke]], [[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]],  Macadoshis, and The Rated R. They released one album, 1994's ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'', before disbanding in 1995. \n\n==History==\n2Pac, Randy \"Stretch\" Walker and Princess Mel formed Thug Life in 1992 with Tyruss \"Little Psycho\" Himes.<ref name=allmusicbio>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p211189|pure_url=yes}} Big Syke bio] at [[Allmusic]]</ref> They recorded a song also titled, \"Thug Life\".  Soon Little Psycho joined the group, under the name Syke. Later Macadoshis and The Rated R joined the group. They signed with Interscope Records and recorded an LP titled ''Thug Life Volume 1''. Tupac\u2019s stepbrother, Mopreme Shakur, later joined the group.\n\n== ''Thug Life: Volume 1'' ==\nOn September 26, 1994, ''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'' was released.\n\nThe first single and video was \"Pour Out a Little Liquor\" which was a Tupac solo song. \n\nTupac performed \"Out on Bail\" at the 1994 Source Awards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Busta Rhymes Says Tupac Dissing A Tribe Called Quest Was A Misunderstanding  |url=http://hiphopwired.com/2012/09/09/busta-rhymes-says-tupac-dissing-a-tribe-called-quest-was-a-misunderstanding-video/ |work=hiphopwired.com |publisher=Hip Hop Wired |date= 9 September 2012 |accessdate= 8 January 2016 |last=Aqua Blanco |first=Alvin}}</ref> The album was originally released on Shakur's label Out Da Gutta. Tupac's mother's label, [[Amaru Entertainment]], has since gained the rights to the album.\n\nThe track \"How Long Will They Mourn Me?\" appeared on 2Pac's 1998 ''Greatest Hits'' album.\n\n''Thug Life: Volume 1'' sold 478,419 copies in the United States as of 2011.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Stretch's death==\nOn November 30, 1995, Stretch died after being shot four times in the back by three men who pulled up alongside his minivan in Queens Village.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rapper Slain After Chase in Queens |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/01/nyregion/rapper-slain-after-chase-in-queens.html |work=nytimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date= 1 December 1995 |accessdate= 1 December 2012 |last=Jones |first=Charisse}}</ref> Stretch was killed exactly one year after 2Pac's 1994 Quad Studio shooting.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biggie, Diddy Knew Tupac Would Be Ambushed In 1994, Alleges Los Angeles Times Reporter |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1583487/biggie-diddy-knew-tupac-would-be-ambushed-in-1994-alleges-los-angeles-times-reporter/ |work=mtv.com |publisher=MTV |date= 16 March 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2016 |last=Reid |first=Shaheem}}</ref>\n\n==Original members==\n* [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] ({{aka}} Makaveli) ({{abbr|d.|died}} 1996)\n* [[Stretch (rapper)|Stretch]] (a.k.a. Big Stretch) (d. 1995)\n* [[Big Syke]] (a.k.a. Mussolini or Little Psycho) (d. 2016)\n* [[Mopreme Shakur|Mopreme]] (a.k.a. Mocedes, The Wycked, Komani or Mo' Khomani)\n* Macadoshis (a.k.a. The Original Mac 10)\n* The Rated R (a.k.a. Super Star)\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[Thug Life: Volume 1]]'' (1994)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Tupac Shakur}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Music|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:African-American musical groups]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rap groups]]\n[[Category:G-funk groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Jive Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thug_Life"}
